A Vehdna member of the secret Stranglers cult in Dreams of Steel, described as a red rumel man: an experienced killer within that tradition. He was subordinate to Narayan Singh and may have belonged to the Changlor band, though that connection is uncertain. During events in Taglios, he served for a time as one of the bodyguards assigned to Lady, placing him among the cultists and foreign allies around her.A taciturn, possibly mute gateman for the Taglian Royal Library during Water Sleeps. He was not a guard and carried no weapon, reflecting the respect given to the library's sanctity in Taglios. His work was simple but visible: opening the wrought iron gate for staff and patrons of the vast institution.A former Annalist of the Black Company who helped write the Book of Kette with Straw, Lees, and Holm during the Company's second century, while it served the Paingod of Cho'n Delor.A supernatural cat-like creature in the retinue of the Imperial new Taken sorceress Mischievous Rain in Port of Shadows. Often resembling an ordinary cat in size and manner, he was distinguished by a third eye set in the center of his forehead. His presence gives the sorceress's household an uncanny familiar-like aspect without reducing him to a normal animal.A historical employer of the Black Company somewhere in the southern continent's murky past, during an episode known as the Revolt of the Chiliarchs, chronicled in the Book of Set by the Annalist Coral. Croaker remembered this period as one of the darkest in Company history, a crisis of honor after the Company took the Archon's gold, though it ultimately held to the letter of its commissions. It remains uncertain exactly when in the Company's long history this service took place.One of the four beautiful daughters of Baron Senjak and a murky figure associated with the beginning of the Domination roughly five centuries before The Black Company. Her aristocratic family may have originated in a far western kingdom of the northern continent, and the sisters were said to vie with one another in loveliness. Fragmentary accounts suggest that Ardath possessed noteworthy sorcerous potential and shared the supernatural allure associated with the women of her bloodline.A Gunni officer from Gondowar who became a prominent military and political figure in Taglios during Soldiers Live. Tall, strikingly handsome, and well regarded for manners as well as competence, he built an excellent reputation in the City Battalions. His abilities as negotiator, strategist, general, and ruler mark him as one of the Protectorate's most capable leaders.The Purohita, or highest priest of Taglios, during Water Sleeps. A Gunni priest of Rhavi-Lemna with wild white hair like an untamed haystack, he sat on the Privy Council of the Protectorate regime. Though formally a royal chaplain, he functioned as the true voice of the priesthoods in council politics.A young woman from the ruling family of the Voroshk world, also known by the nickname Arko. She is presented as a minor sorceress of noble background, with pale coloring and the fair-haired appearance associated with her people. Her listed family includes Shukrat and Gromovol as cousins and Ekaterina as a sister, placing her within the dynastic structure of a powerful magical culture.A homeless man from the squalid Buskin neighborhood of Juniper in Shadows Linger. Like many poor residents of the city, he scrounged for firewood during the arctic winters and found shelter around the Iron Lily tavern, where the barkeeper Marron Shed let him stay in from the cold. He was a marginal but sympathetic figure drawn into the orbit of Shed and the desperate life of the district.A mysterious young girl in the service of the sorceress Mischievous Rain during Port of Shadows, also called Firefly. She appeared to be about six years old, like her twin brother Shin, yet displayed intelligence and sorcerous ability beyond her apparent age. Her small uncanny retinue also included the cat-like Ankou.An elderly, severely nearsighted Gunni copyist and translator at the Taglian Royal Library. He spent much of his life among manuscripts and tomes in the vast institution, where his poor eyesight shaped the quiet routines described in Water Sleeps. His scholarly role connects him to the preservation, copying, and interpretation of written records in Taglios.A travel guide from the jungles of D'loc Aloc who appeared in Shadow Games. Summoned by the monks of the Temple of Travellers' Repose, he and the companion nicknamed Wheezer were engaged to help the Black Company on its journey south. Both were described as short, elderly, wizened natives of their homeland, with Croaker regarding this guide as the more ordinary of the pair.A Nyueng Bao merchant, trader, and smuggler who became a longtime affiliate of the Black Company. His trade ran between Taglios and the swampy delta homeland where the great river meets the ocean, moving goods that ranged from rice to crocodile skins. Because his family handled outside commerce, he was exposed to more foreign influence than most members of his people.One of the new Taken, a group of eight powerful wizards bound to the Lady through the Rite of Taking, whose members dressed identically and were difficult to tell apart. Known to be male, Benefice succeeded the Howler as the Lady's foremost master of the flying carpet, valued especially for his skill in managing large carpets and linking several together into formations, a demanding task admired by his mistress.An ancient maritime city on the northern coast of the southern continent and the oldest of the Jewel Cities, known as their Queen. Governed by rulers called Syndics, it gave its dialect to the Black Company's speech and written Annals. Its long, violent history and landmarks such as the Bastion, Necropolitan Hill, Fortress Island, and the impoverished Groan made it one of the region's most storied cities.A Monitor, or commander, of the Eternal Guard near the Barrowland in the Great Forest. He held authority there during the lifetime of Bomanz, appearing in the biographical narrative connected to The White Rose. Long experience with the disguised wizard made him both an acquaintance and an antagonist, marked by wary familiarity rather than trust.A Black Company member from Opal, recognizable by his wild hair and later known as a noteworthy sergeant. He joined the mercenary brotherhood in Shadow Games after being accused of common theft, entering alongside Sparkle, Red Rudy, and Candles. Like all newcomers he did scut work early on, but his responsibilities grew steadily until he became a well-respected battalion commander in the army of Taglios.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in the first chronicle during its early employment in the Lady's Empire. A white man from the southern continent who had not previously been to the north, he was among the veterans who crossed the Sea of Torments aboard Soulcatcher's giant galley, The Dark Wings, on the way to Opal. He was present in Forsberg province when Raven rescued Darling and Flick from the Limper's men.The nickname of a mysterious sorcerer associated with Rue in the short story Chasing Midnight: The Dark Lord as a Teen. Not a public figure, he concealed a disfigured body beneath black gauze and moved through a vaporous mist that made him difficult to observe clearly. His presentation is secretive, uncanny, and menacing from the outset.A lean, dark-skinned man from the southern continent, originating somewhere north of Taglios. Known for outspoken hatred of priestly castes and cult leaders, he was physically fit, cool-headed in battle, and highly capable with weapons. Alongside Willow Swan and Cordy Mather, he was hired by the Prahbrindrah Drah to help organize armed resistance during the early Shadowmaster conflicts.A powerful sorceress active on the northern continent before the Domination, later associated with the mysterious Master. She is surrounded by vast cardinal-colored magic cloth that can spread across surprising distances, protect her like enchanted clothing, act as strangling tendrils, and allow flight without a carpet or rheitgeistide. Her magic gives her a distinctive and unsettling presence in Shaggy Dog Bridge.One of the new Taken, a group of eight powerful sorcerers bound to the Lady through the Rite of Taking, whose members dressed identically and were difficult to tell apart. Known to be female, Blister served among the Lady's Imperial champions during the events of The White Rose. Her greatest talent was necromancy, an art that in her case extended to divination as well.A Juniperean couple hired by Marron Shed during Shadows Linger to serve as caregivers for his elderly mother, June. They worked after he moved her from the impoverished Buskin neighborhood to a cottage near the Enclosure, the devotional heart of the city. Their role is domestic and local, tied to the fragile respectability he tried to build around his family.A wizard and antiquities digger from Oar, the capital of Forsberg. He excelled in sorcery at the city's Black Campus and married Jasmine, with whom he had a son, Stancil. Drawn to the arcane history of the Barrowland, he settled with his family in the Eternal Guard community and spent decades studying the site while excavating Domination-era artifacts.One of the Ten Who Were Taken, a group of powerful sorcerers bound first to the Dominator during the Domination and later to the Lady's Empire. Enormous even among that dreaded company, he was described as towering, massively muscled, grotesquely strong, and crocodile-faced. His old reputation centered on brutal physical violence as much as wizardry.A TelleKurre king loyal to the Dominator during the Domination. Like other officers of that era, he bore a triangular inset in his forehead that permanently displayed a jewel. His ruby was unique to his royal rank, distinguishing him from lesser servants of the Dominator.A sworn member of the Black Company and one of the three Torque brothers, alongside Stubby and Paddlefoot. Probably from the eastern region of the Lady's Empire, the brothers reported to the Lieutenant and Elmo but remained loyal to Darling and her New White Rose Rebellion. They were known for rough eastern speech, rowdy habits, and a close fraternal bond.A sworn brother of the Black Company, probably a Taglian recruit from the southern continent. Croaker judged him not especially bright and noted poor hearing in his left ear, a trait that shaped how others dealt with him in the Annals. He appears as a rank-and-file soldier during the Company's difficult southern campaigns.An important Inquisitor in Juniper, the frigid city in the far northwest of the northern continent. Originally from the Buskin, he had knowledge of a slum other officials avoided and possessed practical investigative skill. His earlier work in the Jewel Cities also gave him command of their dialect, making him useful when paired with Croaker during Shadows Linger.The poorest and most downtrodden neighborhood of Juniper, situated low in the valley between two arms of the Wolander Mountains. Its residents endured the city's brutal winters in profound poverty, often scavenging for firewood. The Iron Lily tavern and inn stood within the district, whose dangers and hardships were familiar to few city officials.A sworn brother of the Black Company from Chimney, mentioned in the short story Those Who Went Before. Along with Spangler, he was intended to become one of Croaker's physician's apprentices, though both shirked much of that training. His moniker came from a large backside and remained in use even after hard travel through the western wilderness changed his build.A large, very muscular sorcerer serving as bodyguard to Two Dead, a wizard colonel in the Lady's Empire during Port of Shadows. Swift, intelligent, and physically imposing, he was well liked compared with his employer. His Company nickname came from an oversized Adam's apple, shortened from the longer form used by the soldiers around him.A Black Company member from Opal who entered the ranks in Shadow Games alongside Big Bucket, Red Rudy, and Sparkle. Unlike some recruits whose names were assigned by the Company wizards, he already had his moniker when he joined. Croaker noted that the story behind it was long, nonsensical, and not especially interesting.A sworn brother of the Black Company from the southern continent and, for many years, one of its most senior sergeants. Croaker described him as low-key, socially skilled, and effective without showiness, a contrast to many rougher Company men. During the band's time in Aloe, he ranked near the top of the command structure beneath the Lieutenant.A Rebel leader active during the Port of Shadows chapter also released as Smelling Danger. Reportedly a cousin of Whisper, he operated in the conflict around Aloe while the Black Company was garrisoned there. His role places him among the opposition figures connected to Rebel military action against the Company in that region.A Nyueng Bao necromancer mentioned briefly in She Is the Darkness. He was the father of Hong Tray, the last true priestess of her people, and an ancestor within a family line important to Nyueng Bao memory. His practice was discussed rarely and with mild embarrassment, suggesting that necromancy was frowned upon in that culture.The leader of the Black Company during Croaker's first two chronicles, known by no personal name. Born in one of the Jewel Cities, he had been a professional soldier before joining the mercenary brotherhood and eventually rising to command. A master strategist, brusque with his own men yet unflappable around dangerous sorcerers, he relied on strong subordinates such as the Lieutenant, Elmo, Candy, and Mercy.A sworn brother of the Black Company from the southern continent and one of its sergeants in the first chronicle. He served among the veteran noncommissioned leaders under the Captain, alongside figures such as Candy and Match. His role is practical and military rather than biographical, with no extended personal history recorded.A soldier of the Eternal Guard from a northern farming family and the main narrator of The Silver Spike. He disliked farm life, his given name, and the parents who burdened him with it, eventually leaving home in search of military adventure. His service brought him to the Barrowland, where the Guard watched over the lethal graveyard containing the Dominator and his demons.Strange, reclusive humanoid denizens of the black castle of Juniper in Shadows Linger. Their faces were described in sharp angles and shadows, with lustrous olive coldness and softly luminous eyes, and they wore black hooded clothing. Their exact nature is not fully explained, though the details suggest summoned beings or demons tied to the castle's supernatural presence.A Taglian ambassador mentioned in Bleak Seasons alongside Ranjalpirindi. He represented the Prahbrindrah Drah during political dealings connected to Dejagore, placing him among the Prince's diplomatic agents. His role is courtly and political rather than military, tied to Taglios's attempts to influence events around the Black Company.One of the most influential chief priests of the majority Gunni faith in Taglios during the Books of the South. Bald and dressed in scarlet robes, he stood among the city's powerful religious figures and was regarded by Smoke as one of its most important men. His position placed him amid rival priestly factions, including other Gunni leaders and counterparts from the Shadar and Vehdna faiths.A high-ranking Gunni bureaucrat of Taglios during Water Sleeps, holding the office of Inspector-General of the Records. As a member of the Privy Council, he belonged to the administrative elite of the Protectorate. Ancient, hairless, lean, and severe, he had expanded a once-minor civic role into authority over finances and public works.The administrative capital and personal palace of the Lady's Empire, in the northern continent. An immense featureless black cube of imported basalt — by far the largest structure in the north — it is surrounded by strewn basalt boulders in every direction save a single perfectly manicured approach, funnelling all land access to a controlled point. Manned by the Lady's functionaries and the Tower Guard, it encloses a smaller inner Tower within one-third of its volume. It serves as the customary east-west demarcation of the Empire, with the Salient and Forsberg to the north and the Jewel City of Opal and the Sea of Torments to the south.A young auburn-haired bandit woman and inexperienced witch who plays a central role in Bone Eaters and Chasing Midnight: The Dark Lord as a Teen. Her family includes a twin brother, an older brother, and several male cousins connected to the same bandit clan west of Rue. She is also presented as a medic trainee, learning practical healing work alongside her minor sorcery.A teenage bandit and inexperienced low-magnitude wizard appearing in Bone Eaters and Chasing Midnight: The Dark Lord as a Teen. Auburn-haired and twelve minutes younger than his twin sister, he belonged to a clan west of Rue with an older brother and several male cousins. Hard weather, pests, poor crops, and relentless tax collectors helped push the family into amateur banditry.A female sergeant of the Black Company during its stationing in Aloe, counted among only nine women in the brotherhood at that time. Physically more formidable than many male soldiers, she had a difficult relationship with Croaker, who called her his near nemesis. Her duties included disciplined supervision inside the Company's compound, where her record-keeping and vigilance mattered.A teenage bandit and loyal cousin of Chasing Midnight and Chasing Moonlight in the On The Long Run story arc. Among the cousins, he is the one most often seen directly at Midnight's side. His clan came from west of Rue and was pushed into amateur banditry by bad weather, pests, poor crops, and relentless tax collectors.A major harbor city sprawling across the slopes of the Salada Peninsula, which projects from the western coast of the northern continent into the Gap. It lies south of Meadenvil, beyond the lesser coastal cities of Tagline, Needle, and Shaker. Poverty was pervasive enough that Croaker believed even broken glass would be gathered for its tiny resale value, while powerful local institutions included the Houses of Istven and the Seamen's Guild.A haunted ruin above the Second Cataract on the southern continent's great river, its silhouette likened by Willow Swan to a heap of skulls. Two centuries before Croaker's time, the tyrant Paingod ruled it and employed the Black Company against the Triplet Cities in the Pastel Wars. The conflict left all four cities ruined and the surrounding land so haunted that people and animals avoided it.A Children of the Dead soldier from Hsien who appears in Soldiers Live as a senior military figure associated with the Black Company. He was a respected veteran in his native world before joining the outsider mercenaries, likely after service to one of Hsien's many warlords. His roles included brigade command and later general staff work, reflecting disciplined professional experience.A cabal of powerful sorcerers who led the Rebel armies against the Lady's Empire. Drawn largely from the Empire's eastern borderlands, it organized major campaigns across the northern continent. Prominent members included Raker, Whisper, and Harden, and the Circle devoted considerable resources to finding the prophesied reincarnation of the White Rose.A man from Oar and brother of Tokar, Glory, and the young Snoopy. He appears in the biographical narrative surrounding Bomanz in The White Rose, placing him among the families connected to the Barrowland and its history. Little else about his background or personality is recorded.A native of the Jewel City of Beryl and brother of Loftus and Longinus. After service in the Urban Cohorts, he joined the Black Company in Shadow Games and quickly became valuable for technical expertise. The three siblings established themselves as indispensable engineers, artillery specialists, and architects within the mercenary brotherhood.A historical Annalist of the Black Company from an unspecified number of generations before Croaker. He was remembered for writing the Book of Set, one of the volumes of the Annals. That work primarily concerned the Company's service to the Archon of Bone during the Revolt of the Chiliarchs, a dark and morally difficult period in its remembered history.Captain of a secret Rebel cell in Tanner during The White Rose and one of Darling's informants. Known for contacts throughout the city, he served as eyes and ears for the New White Rose Rebellion against the Lady's Empire. Croaker knew his name by reputation before meeting him, recognizing the value of his long-running intelligence work.A wanderer from Roses who crossed paths with the Black Company in Shadow Games. Calm, patient, and steady, he was close friends with Willow Swan and Blade after years of travel through the southern continent. The three were hired by the Prahbrindrah Drah to help organize Taglios's first armed resistance against the early Shadowmaster invasions.A young new recruit of the Black Company in Aloe during the short stories later collected in Port of Shadows. He appears around off-duty life in the city, including games of tonk with older veterans at the Dark Horse tavern. His role is that of a junior brother learning the rhythms and obligations of the mercenary band.A sworn brother of the Black Company present in Aloe during Port of Shadows. Literate in Aloen, he was useful for work involving local written records and public documents. His role reflects how practical language skills could make an otherwise minor soldier valuable during a stationing in unfamiliar territory.An elderly stable keeper in the major city of Oar and a local Rebel during The Black Company. His stable served as lodging for the Company's regular supply patrols from Deal, making him a small but useful figure in the city's wartime networks. As a civilian tradesman, his politics tied him to the local opposition.A physically massive thug in Krage's gang during Shadows Linger, working in the Buskin, Juniper's poorest slum. He served as the gangster's most intimidating enforcer, though Marron Shed regarded him as less pointlessly cruel than some of the others. His big brown cow eyes and sheer size made him memorable among the local underworld figures.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in Shadows Linger during service to the Lady's Empire in Juniper. He was selected for the advance team flown into the city ahead of the main body, a trusted group led by Elmo and including Croaker, Goblin, Pawnbroker, Kingpin, Otto, and other veterans. His role marks him as a reliable soldier used for sensitive assignments.One of the new Taken, a group of eight powerful wizards bound to the Lady through the Rite of Taking, whose members dressed identically and were difficult to tell apart; Croaker was never able to determine this individual's sex. The Creeper was stationed at the city of Frost during the Lady's encirclement of the Plain of Fear and served among her Imperial champions during the events of The White Rose.A sworn brother of the Black Company active during employment in the Lady's Empire. Before that northern service, he had been with the band in Beryl and crossed the Sea of Torments aboard Soulcatcher's giant galley, The Dark Wings, to Opal. His recorded role is that of a rank-and-file veteran present during the first chronicle's early imperial campaigns.A central Black Company figure across the Books of the North, South, and Glittering Stone. The Company's physician and a respected Annalist, he narrates many of its chronicles. Born near trade routes south of Padora, he is tall, scarred, skeptical of religion, naturally curious, and gifted at languages.A sworn brother of the Black Company active before the first book and during the band's contract with the Syndic of Beryl. His ironic name came from being bald. Croaker's medical attention to him, including recurring treatment for crabs, gives the character a coarse barracks-life texture typical of the Company's rank and file.A sworn brother of the Black Company from Chimney, recruited among the city's young lowlifes during the On The Long Run arc. He appears in Leta of the Thousand Sorrows and is associated with other new recruits from the same city. His recorded duty is modest but practical: serving as a messenger alongside the archer Zeb.A doctor from Taglios and personal physician to the Radisha Drah. She came from a family of physicians and was highly regarded for her skill, with the Princess dryly noting that even male colleagues admitted she was marginally competent. Almost certainly Gunni, she is described as tiny and wearing a pink sari during her brief appearance in Dreams of Steel.A notorious general from Beryl at some point in the city's long history. His infamy rested on having nearly destroyed the city, and the people still shuddered to speak his name in later times. Croaker used that reputation as the basis for a joking exclamation during The Black Company.A blonde, deaf-mute girl from Forsberg who becomes closely connected to Raven and the Black Company in the early chronicles. She communicates through finger speech, a skill shared with Silent and gradually understood by Croaker. Her presence around the mercenary brotherhood is quiet but emotionally important, especially because others take on protective roles toward her.A female cult figurehead of the Stranglers, revered as the Foretold in connection with the goddess Kina. Raised under the guardianship of Narayan Singh and later linked to the Khadidas, she was dedicated from childhood to transcribing the Books of the Dead. Her role is religious, magical, and deeply bound to the cult's hopes for the Year of the Skulls.A worker in the Palace of Taglios during Water Sleeps, subordinate to the corrupt subassistant housekeeper Jaul Barundandi. His role involved collecting kickbacks from poverty-stricken daily laborers inside the Palace. The character reflects the petty graft and exploitation present within the Protectorate's household bureaucracy.A Nyueng Bao swordsmith who crafted the excellent blade Ash Wand about four centuries before Bleak Seasons. His hallmark near the hilt identified the weapon as his work, a detail recognized by Croaker when Uncle Doj displayed the sword in the Palace of Taglios. The brief reference places him among the respected ancient craftsmen of Nyueng Bao martial culture.The great tyrant of the northern continent and ruler of the Domination, which he controlled for roughly a century through sorcery, fear, force of will, and vast armies. He enslaved ten powerful wizards as his generals, the Ten Who Were Taken, while his wife the Lady helped shape the imperial order. His defeat and imprisonment beneath the Barrowland left his name as one of the defining threats in northern history.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned during early employment in the Lady's Empire. He had previously been with the band in Beryl and crossed the Sea of Torments aboard Soulcatcher's giant galley, The Dark Wings, to Opal. His role is that of a veteran rank-and-file soldier present during the first chronicle's northern campaigns.A great winged guardian of the Barrowland in the Great Forest, watching that dangerous place for more than 370 years. Of immense stature, with green eyes described as ancient, wise, merciless, arrogant, mocking, and contemptuous, it was the only individual of its kind mentioned in the Annals. Its agelessness and extreme loyalty suggest a demonic rather than natural origin.A type of giant demon bound to the Lady, appearing briefly in The Black Company. The entities' size, speed, and power indicated that they were available only to conjurers of the highest magnitudes. Croaker's Annals describe one such monster as luminescent, emphasizing its supernatural and dangerous presence.The hereditary castle of Juniper's dukes, occupied by Duke Zimerlan during Shadows Linger. It stood on the highest ridge of the southern arm of the Wolander Mountains, across the Port River valley from the mysterious black castle. Like much of Juniper, the palace had fallen into conspicuous disrepair.A sworn brother of the Black Company from Aloe who served as Croaker's apprentice physician during Port of Shadows. He learned quickly and was especially valued for veterinary experience, a skill useful amid the livestock gathered during the stay in his hometown. When the band prepared to move on, he chose to remain there rather than continue with them.A universally respected veteran sergeant of the Black Company during the Books of the North. Croaker described him as sharp despite the appearance of a big, dumb country soldier, and regarded him as both spokesman for the enlisted men and closest friend. Earlier hints suggest a background involving farming, mines, and long service before the first chronicle begins.The devotional heart of Juniper, the Enclosure was a walled park of pine groves containing the headquarters of the city's Custodians. Beneath it lay the famous Catacombs, where generations of Juniper's dead were interred, while Duke Zimerlan's palace of Duretile stood high above on the southern ridge of the Wolander Mountains. Though remembered as respectable and park-like in earlier years, it had become threadbare by the time of Shadows Linger.A Nar warrior from Gea-Xle and one of the thirty-three members of that elite caste who joined the Black Company in Shadow Games. His background places him among the disciplined black warriors whose martial culture made a strong impression on the mercenary brotherhood. He represents the influx of Nar soldiers from the southern city.A powerful Imperial sorcerer who represented the empire's leadership in the beleaguered city of Oar during The Silver Spike. He was noted for honesty, fair play, and coolheaded conduct, unusual traits in the political and magical struggles around him. His wealthy, ostentatiously colored clothing led observers to compare him to a popinjay, clown, or peacock.An advanced sorcery employed by the Lady, used as a tool of interrogation across her Empire. It manifests as a gigantic yellow eyeball growing out from the Lady's face, surrounded by an all-encompassing lemon-colored glow and accompanied by an unsettling humming sound. The Eye compels truth from any subject: it cannot be deceived, can surface forgotten or unconsciously suppressed information, and is applied to Rebel prisoners and Imperial functionaries alike — all the way up to the Ten Who Were Taken, none of whom are exempt. Being examined by the Eye is universally described in the Annals as a harrowing experience; some individuals subjected to the "deep probe" come out listless and never recover. Despite its fearsome reputation, the Eye is not omniscient: the Lady must approach it with specific questions and familiarity with the subject, and it does not permit outright mind-reading — it only ensures the subject cannot lie.One of the original Ten Who Were Taken, the powerful sorcerers who served the Dominator during the Domination and later the Lady's Empire. Specific details about him are scarce because Croaker did not encounter him personally. His sigil was a simple circle, perhaps representing a zero, and his known military reputation included command activity far from the Company's immediate viewpoint.A teenage bandit and loyal cousin of Chasing Midnight and Chasing Moonlight in the On The Long Run story arc. Among the cousins, he is the most dangerous, noted for proficiency with a crossbow and greater independence than Chick. His clan came from west of Rue and was driven into amateur banditry by hardship, poor crops, pests, and relentless tax collectors.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in Bone Eaters, part of the On The Long Run arc. He helped lead a haggard-looking scout group at the head of its refugee train in the western wilderness. His role places him among the forward soldiers responsible for contact, screening, and first response during difficult travel.An immensely powerful demon entity located at the geographic center of the Plain of Fear. Appearing as a deciduous tree with a massive trunk, he is worshipped as a god by the region's sparse human tribes and commands its strange creatures, including menhirs, windwhales, mantas, reversed centaurs, walking trees, and other beings. Change storms on the Plain are speculated to be his dreams.An unnamed sorcerer of immense magnitude, comparable to the Dominator, who subjugated a northern region in ages before the Domination. Already legendary in the Lady's youth, he was defeated by forces described as the side of light and buried alive beneath what became the Plain of Fear. Father Tree was summoned as a godlike sapling from another plane to hold him underground with its roots.A young but powerful Rebel sorceress who fought against the Lady's Empire in The Black Company. Recently promoted to the Circle of Eighteen when first mentioned in the Annals, she belonged to the rebellion's elite magical leadership. She and the fellow sorcerer Journey were newly married, linking two rising members of the Circle.A sworn brother of the Black Company from the southern continent, mentioned in Bleak Seasons. He served during the defense of Dejagore and held messenger duty at the city's walls. His brief appearance presents him as a practical rank-and-file soldier used for urgent communication during a dangerous military posting.A demon also known in dormant form as an obsidian serpent. It is described with vast dark wings, red eyes like forge windows, glossy talons like obsidian knives, and a mouth filled with sharp dark teeth. The creature's fiery, winged form and artifact-like resting state mark it as one of the more visually striking supernatural entities in The Silver Spike.The leader of the ruling family of the Voroshk world in Soldiers Live. A prince and elder patriarch, he was brother to Nashun the Researcher and father to Shukrat, placing him near the center of Voroshk dynastic authority. Like others of that family, he wore priceless shefsepoken robes and traveled by personal rheitgeistide.A historical Shadowmaster in the Land of Unknown Shadows, remembered chiefly through titles rather than a personal name. He is credited with creating many of the stranger Unknown Shadows inhabiting Hsien by reshaping feral shadows from the glittering plain. His work gave those beings greater intelligence and physical traits drawn from natural creatures.An elderly man from Forsberg and grandfather of Darling in The Black Company. After entering the orbit of Raven and the mercenary brotherhood, he traveled as a camp follower and felt indebted to those who had helped him and his granddaughter. He shared Rebel stories and prophecies with Pickles, despite the Company's service to the Lady's Empire.A massive, dense evergreen forest on the northern continent, situated east of the Salient, west of the major city of Lords, and south of Oar. Its interior included groves of huge, ancient evergreens and offered enough seclusion to conceal camps and travelers. The forest's position made it a significant wilderness between important northern territories of the Lady's Empire.The northernmost province of the Lady's Empire in the northern continent, Forsberg was its own independent kingdom before the Lady's consolidation wars. The province's capital and largest city is Oar, located in its northernmost reaches; the next most important site is Deal, a major fortress south of Oar. The native language is Forsberger. Forsberg borders the vast Great Forest to the north and the province of the Salient to the south. It became a hotbed of Rebel activity in the war against the Lady's Empire, with the general Raker driving significant Imperial losses there.Supernatural predators from the equatorial jungles of D'loc Aloc, commonly called wereleopards. They appear human by day and become black leopards by night, hunting people for blood and organs. Their speed makes ordinary weapons nearly useless, while only sorcerers of great magnitude can harm them reliably with magic.A tall K'Hlata warrior from the savannah south of D'loc Aloc who joined the Black Company alongside his brother Geek in Shadow Games. Armed with javelins, a long-bladed spear, and a black-and-white hide shield, he came from a striking martial culture that impressed Croaker physically. Goblin supplied the nickname, though the birth name was Heart-of-the-Lion.An imp from the demon worlds, diminutive in stature but proportioned like an adult. A powerful supernatural trickster, he could disappear and reappear instantly, cleanse poison from human blood, and understand or interpret seemingly any language. He disliked being called a demon, insisted on the more precise term imp, and was old enough that Smoke speculated he might be ten thousand years of age.A tall K'Hlata warrior from the savannah south of D'loc Aloc who joined the Black Company alongside his brother Freak in Shadow Games. Armed with javelins, a long-bladed spear, and a black-and-white hide shield, he moved with the same rhythmic precision as his sibling. Goblin supplied the nickname, though the birth name was Claw-of-the-Lion.The High Priest of the Shadar religion in Taglios when the Black Company first arrived in Shadow Games. He competed with the Prahbrindrah Drah and the high priests of other major faiths for influence in the city. His personal patron was Hada, goddess of Death, Destruction, and Corruption, and he commanded the subcult known as the Children of Hada.An old, one-eyed, corrupt moneylender operating in the Buskin, Juniper's poorest district, during Shadows Linger. He dealt with Marron Shed, owner of the Iron Lily, and moved within the same grim local economy as gangsters, debtors, and desperate residents. His role is that of a predatory financier in the slum's underworld.A woman from Oar and sister of Tokar, Clete, and the young Snoopy. Engaged to Stancil, the son of Bomanz and Jasmine, she appears in the earlier Barrowland narrative recounted in The White Rose. Her family connections place her within the circle surrounding Bomanz's history.One of the Black Company's wizards during the modern Annals, an elderly, short, skinny man with a high-pitched voice and a grin often compared to a frog or toad. His magic favored illusions and sleeping spells, making him valuable for reconnaissance and infiltration. His long-running feud with One-Eye was notorious, elaborate, and ultimately an expression of friendship.An influential sorceress in the Lady's Empire during The Silver Spike and twin sister of Spidersilk. She trained in magic at the Tower at Charm and dressed in black clothing in imitation of the Ten Who Were Taken. Her profile reflects the ambition and style of Imperial wizards operating below the legendary magnitude of the Taken themselves.A young nobleman and wizard from the ruling family of the Voroshk world in Soldiers Live. He was brother to Sedvod, son of Nashun the Researcher, and nephew of the First Father, with cousins including Arkana, Shukrat, and Magadan. Raised amid immense privilege, he belonged to a magical culture defined by shefsepoken robes, rheitgeistiden, and rigid status.One of the mysterious creatures appointed to watch over the sacred Catacombs of Juniper. The Annals describe the Guardians only vaguely as monsters, and they seem to remain within the subterranean chambers rather than roaming the city. Their role connects them to the Custodians, who maintained the Catacombs and deposited the newly deceased there.Two sworn members of the underground Black Company mentioned in Water Sleeps, one of whom carried the nickname Sin. They were from the southern continent and almost certainly veterans of the Kiaulune wars, though their exact race or city of origin is not specified. Like others in Taglios, they balanced ordinary work with Company affairs handled in off-hours.A chatty ten-year-old orphan boy from Aloe in Port of Shadows. Creative and fond of storytelling, he impressed Croaker by enlivening folktales with sympathetic embellishments. Though destined for the celibate priesthood of the Occupoa cult, he found that future unappealing and instead gravitated toward gossip, companionship, and local curiosity.A female member of the Black Company in Port of Shadows and sister to Hika Nolet. The sisters were among the very small number of women in the mercenary brotherhood and dressed in men's clothing. They were evidently disliked by many others, giving them a sharp and difficult reputation within the ranks.One of the longest-serving members of the Black Company, usually found alongside Otto. Born in Rebosa on the southern continent, he had a polytheistic upbringing and became known as a superb scout and expert shot with a sniper's crossbow. Quiet, unsentimental, and hard to kill, he was one of the iconic veterans whose endurance symbolized the Company's survival.One of the Ten Who Were Taken, a powerful sorcerer and general in the Lady's war against the Rebel Circle of Eighteen. Improbably tall and lean, he bore the swollen, purpled neck and bent head suggested by his name, with a face frozen in a strangled rictus. He could communicate in TelleKurre and was especially associated with countering airborne pastel sorcery.A male sorcerer and one of the most powerful members of the Circle of Eighteen in The Black Company. A major Rebel general, he was connected by family to Whisper and Raker, and was known for a vile, volatile, unpredictable temper. Croaker described his projected likeness as a giant bearded face with tangled orange hair and one eye half closed by a livid scar.One of the most influential figures in Juniper during Shadows Linger. As senior Custodian, he was responsible for the Catacombs, the city's most sacred place, where the dead had been interred for centuries. Familiar with Duke Zimerlan and the city's highest circles, he embodied Juniper's religious authority and its anxiety over the black castle.A teenage bandit and loyal cousin of Chasing Midnight and Chasing Moonlight in the On The Long Run story arc. Brother to Yuko and less often at Midnight's side than Chick or Fade, he belonged to the same clan west of Rue. Had the teenagers not been separated from their homeland by ill fortune, he would have become her husband.A red-haired female member of the Black Company in Port of Shadows and sister to Guust Nolet. The sisters were among the very small number of women in the mercenary brotherhood and dressed in men's clothing. They were evidently disliked by many others, giving them a sharp and difficult reputation within the ranks.A former Annalist of the Black Company who helped write the Book of Kette with Straw, Lees, and Agrip during the Company's second century, while it served the Paingod of Cho'n Delor.A horse doctor among the Eternal Guard during The White Rose. He was the closest thing to a physician in the Barrowland before the great conflict there, giving him a practical medical role among soldiers rather than formal status as a doctor. His presence shows the Guard's rough, provincial approach to care and diagnosis.An influential Nyueng Bao De Duang leader and their last true priestess. Elderly and physically frail, she retained a sharp intelligence that Murgen immediately recognized. Wife of Ky Dam, mother of Ky Gota, and grandmother of Ky Sahra, she stood at the center of a family whose ties shaped relations between the Nyueng Bao and the Black Company.One of the Ten Who Were Taken, an ancient wizard of great knowledge and power. He appeared as a tiny, masked man wrapped tightly in dirty indigo rags, notorious for random, chilling, uncontrollable screams. Best known for creating magical artifacts, especially flying carpets, he was an unrivaled pilot and often floated in the air even when not using one.Supernatural entities that haunted the Village of Hungry Ghosts west of Rue in Bone Eaters. They emitted a siren call that lured victims into an irrational trance, making the ruins taboo and widely avoided. Croaker was uncertain of their origin, but suspected old wizardry or a dawn-time god; they could exist as discorporate spirits or as incarnate possessors of living bodies.A corporal in the Eternal Guard during the lifetime of Bomanz, appearing in the flashback biographical narrative in The White Rose. He answered to Monitor Besand and was familiar with Bomanz as a local antiquities digger. His role places him among the ordinary Guardsmen stationed near the Barrowland and its dangerous traditions.A jamadar in the Stranglers cult, leading the Ineld band of Vehdna extraction from Hatchpur State. Narayan Singh described his longstanding feud with Kowran, a rival jamadar of the Twana band from the same region but of Shadar background. The dispute involved accusations of heresy and poaching, and Lady interpreted it as resembling a criminal territorial conflict.An influential priest of the Vehdna religious, racial, and cultural group in Taglios during Dreams of Steel. He stood among the city's leading cult authorities at a time when the major priesthoods competed for power and resources. His position made him one of the prominent domestic opponents of Lady's efforts to assert military authority in the city.A tavern and inn in Juniper's impoverished Buskin neighborhood, owned by Marron Shed as the third generation of his family to keep it. Shed lived there with his blind, elderly mother June, who helped clean its upstairs rooms. The establishment served poor locals as well as travelers and became an important gathering place in Shadows Linger.One of the thirty-three Nar who joined the Black Company in Shadow Games. Though his Company rank is not specified, he became a general in the Taglian army under the Prahbrindrah Drah, answering directly to Lady as the Company's Lieutenant. His role places him among the Nar soldiers who rose into command during the Shadowmaster wars.The nickname of a Monitor, or commander, of the Eternal Guard near the Barrowland in the Great Forest, appearing in the flashback biographical narrative attributed to Bomanz in The White Rose. Reputedly the black sheep of a wealthy family from Oar, he was sent to the Barrowland by his uncle in a gesture resembling exile, replacing the veteran Monitor Besand. His arrival was excessive and out of step with the austere post he was taking over, and he struggled from the start to win the respect or obedience of the Eternal Guardsmen under his command.The second-highest-ranking priest of the Shadar religion in Taglios when the Black Company first arrives in Shadow Games. His personal patron was Khadi, the Shadar avatar of Kina, and he was notably tall, physically imposing, and fair-skinned by Taglian standards. He was an early and useful ally of the Black Company in the city.A high-ranking and wealthy general in the Lady's Empire during The Black Company, considered by Croaker to hold about as much status and influence as one could without being one of the Ten Who Were Taken. Overweight, aristocratic, and dismissive of those he considered beneath his station, he was known to socialize among senior Imperial officers in the high-society circles of Opal, one of the Jewel Cities.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in the short story Leta of the Thousand Sorrows, part of the On The Long Run arc. One of several young recruits drawn from the city of Chimney, he spoke in a pidgin dialect that Croaker, the Company's Annalist, found difficult to understand.The wife of the wizard Bomanz and mother of Stancil, whose account provided the basis for the narrative about her husband in The White Rose. Born to a family in Oar, she followed Bomanz to the isolated Eternal Guard community near the Barrowland. She resented exchanging comfort and status for hardship in the Great Forest but remained devoted to him and protected his secrets.The subassistant housekeeper of the Palace of Taglios during Water Sleeps, and a devout Gunni of the cult of Khusa. His role was to hire day laborers from the lower classes for cleaning work as part of the Protectorate's charity program, a position he regularly abused to extract sexual favors and kickbacks from those under him, often collected through his subordinate Del Mukharjee. His wife Narita also worked within the Palace.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in the Annals of the first chronicle, distinct from the Nyueng Bao swordsman of the same name. Before serving in the Lady's Empire, he had been with the Company in Beryl and crossed the Sea of Torments aboard Soulcatcher's giant galley, The Dark Wings, to Opal.A Nyueng Bao man born Cho Dai Cho, and one of Uncle Doj's pupils in the Path of the Sword swordsmanship tradition, distinct from a Black Company soldier of the same name. He and a group of fellow swordsmen pledged themselves as protectors to the Black Company's Old Crew, with JoJo specifically assigned to guard the wizard One-Eye, though the two were rarely seen together.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in the Annals of the first chronicle, whom Croaker described as professionally sarcastic and sour. Before serving in the Lady's Empire, he had been with the Company in Beryl and crossed the Sea of Torments aboard Soulcatcher's giant galley, The Dark Wings, to Opal.An apprentice physician and sworn brother of the Black Company during the events of the short stories Shaggy Dog Bridge and Bone Eaters, part of the On The Long Run arc. He served among Croaker's small group of apprentice physicians during the Company's travels through the western wilderness.A young but powerful Rebel sorcerer who fought against the Lady's Empire in The Black Company, recently promoted into the Rebel leadership known as the Circle of Eighteen at the time of his introduction in the Annals. He and his wife Feather, a fellow Rebel sorcerer, were newlywed at this point in the story.The elderly, blind mother of Marron Shed, owner of the Iron Lily tavern in the frigid city of Juniper, during Shadows Linger. She raised her son Marron in the impoverished Buskin district and, despite her blindness and arthritic bones, continued to help however she could around their home above the bar.A large, independent harbor city-state in the far northwest of the northern continent, built in the Port River valley between two snow-topped arms of the Wolander Mountains. Ruled by Duke Zimerlan from Duretile, it was known for frigid weather and a death-centered religion whose Custodians interred the deceased in immense Catacombs. Notable districts and landmarks included the Buskin, Iron Lily, Enclosure, and the shunned black castle.An Annalist of the Black Company and one of Croaker's predecessors in that role, alongside Miller Ladora. Their tenures were notoriously lax, leaving relatively little from that era of Company history preserved in the Annals beyond what later Annalists reconstructed from oral tradition and survivors' memories.A sworn brother of the Black Company in Water Sleeps, and a Shadowlander of the Vehdna religion. He served loyally under Sleepy and Ky Sahra as part of their underground network of Company operatives active in and around Taglios.A demon utterly loyal to the goddess Kina, and an antagonist of the Black Company during Soldiers Live, the final Book of Glittering Stone. The entity had been imprisoned for millennia alongside Kina beneath Shivetya's fortress at the center of the glittering plain, and worked toward Kina's ultimate goal, the Year of the Skulls.A city of Kina cult-worshipers, and the place of origin of the Free Companies of Khatovar—most prominently the Black Company itself—which were created there and sent across the glittering plain into the homeworld and other worlds. Their mission was to find the best location for a sacred religious rite called the Year of the Skulls. Over the centuries that followed, the meaning and nature of Khatovar were entirely lost to later generations of Black Company soldiers. After the Battle of the Barrowland, Croaker vowed to return the Company's Annals to this mysterious origin, setting the course for the Company's long southward odyssey. The name carries translations in different sources: "Khadi's Throne", "Place from which Khadi went forth", or simply "Khadi's gate."A member of the Nar, the elite warrior caste of the city of Gea-Xle, and one of thirty-two Nar who joined Mogaba on the Black Company's pilgrimage back to their ancestral roots in Shadow Games. He fought as a Company soldier during the early Shadowmaster wars.A sworn brother of the Black Company originating from Taglios, who rose to the rank of sergeant. Murgen noted that his name Pete derived from the center syllable of a lengthy Gunni godname, a naming quirk that led another Company man, Lhopal Pete, to adopt a distinguishing nickname.A vastly powerful female entity imprisoned for millennia beneath Shivetya's fortress at the center of the glittering plain. Worshipped under many names, including Dark Mother, Mother of Night, Queen of Darkness, and Khat-hi, she is revered by the Stranglers and other southern cults. The Free Companies of Khatovar, ancestors of the Black Company, were founded by her worshippers.A sworn brother of the Black Company, nicknamed King, who appears in Port of Shadows and Shadows Linger. A veteran soldier respected by Croaker for his skill with a sword despite a reputation for laziness, he served for a time in Sergeant Kragler's platoon before later duties alongside Croaker, Pawnbroker, and the Company wizards One-Eye, Goblin, and Silent.A major within the Eternal Guard during The White Rose, serving under the Monitor Colonel Sweet. His only recorded action was being sent on an arrest mission to the city of Oar.A sworn brother of the Black Company who held the rank of sergeant by the time of She Is the Darkness, likely a native of Taglios given his rise through the ranks during the Shadowmaster wars.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in the Annals of the first chronicle. Before serving in the Lady's Empire, he had been with the Company in Beryl and crossed the Sea of Torments aboard Soulcatcher's giant galley, The Dark Wings, to Opal.A jamadar in the Stranglers cult, leading the Twana band of Shadar extraction from Hatchpur State. Narayan Singh described his longstanding feud with Iluk, a rival jamadar of the Ineld band from the same region but of Vehdna background, involving mutual accusations of heresy and poaching that Lady interpreted as resembling a criminal territorial conflict.A prominent and ruthless gangster who controlled much of the Buskin, the poorest slum of the frigid city of Juniper, during Shadows Linger. He lived in conspicuous wealth compared to the impoverished surroundings of his criminal operation.A platoon sergeant of the Black Company mentioned in the short story Tides Elba, part of Port of Shadows. Kingpin served for a time as one of his subordinate soldiers.A pair of black-haired teenage girls of slight stature who assisted the new Taken sorceress Mischievous Rain in Port of Shadows, referred to collectively by Croaker as the hunter girls. They were Tides Elba copy girls tasked with tracking down others like themselves who had gone feral, working alongside the Black Company during operations in Aloe and the Ghost Country.The elected Speaker of the Nyueng Bao De Duang people, husband of the seer Hong Tray, father of Ky Gota, and grandfather of Ky Sahra and Thai Dei. Fluent in both the Nyueng Bao and Taglian languages, he worked to fulfill his wife's prophecies despite resistance from within his own family and people.A prominent member of the Nyueng Bao tribe, daughter of the priestess Hong Tray and the Speaker Ky Dam, mother of Ky Sahra and Thai Dei, and grandmother of Tobo and To Tan. Known within the Black Company as Mother Gota, she was notorious for her bitter, complaining personality and her reputation as an exceptionally poor cook, and, despite her advanced age and physical ailments, she was also one of Uncle Doj's students in the Path of the Sword.A strikingly beautiful young Nyueng Bao woman from the delta south of Taglios. The daughter of Ky Gota, sister of Thai Dei, and granddaughter of Speaker Ky Dam and the priestess Hong Tray, she belonged to a prominent family within her people. Sahra inherited witchcraft through that family line; in Nyueng Bao usage, Ky is her family name and Sahra her personal name.A sworn brother of the Black Company literate in the Aloen language, present in Aloe during the events of Port of Shadows. He may have been related to Sana Ans, a local servant girl who worked as one of the cooks for Mischievous Rain.The ruler of much of the northern continent for generations, first alongside her husband the Dominator during the Domination and later as empress in her own right. An extremely powerful sorceress, brilliant strategist, and natural leader, she is remembered ambiguously in the Annals as either a defense against greater evils or evil itself. She employed the Black Company through her sister and legate, Soulcatcher, during the wars against the Circle of Eighteen.A woman identified in the disputed records of Port of Shadows as one of the four Senjak sisters of the Domination era. The surviving accounts disagree about her precise place within that famous family, leaving even her identity uncertain. She belongs to the obscure history surrounding the Senjaks rather than to the better-documented modern Annals.A captain in the army of the Ten Who Were Taken called the Limper, in the Lady's Empire, reporting directly to Colonel Zouad. He appears during the Black Company's early service to the Empire in The Black Company.A Taglian general appearing in both the retrospective and current narratives of Bleak Seasons. He belonged to the high-caste Gunni community, the largest of Taglios's three major religious and ethnic groups. His rank placed him among the city's senior military figures during the conflict surrounding Dejagore.A sworn brother of the Black Company from the Shadowlands, mentioned in She Is the Darkness. Originally a prisoner of war, he gradually earned a place within the Company through scutwork before taking the Company oath.One of the new Taken, a group of eight powerful wizards bound to the Lady through the Rite of Taking, whose members dressed identically and were difficult to tell apart; Croaker was never able to determine this individual's sex. Learned was stationed at the town of Rue during the Lady's encirclement of the Plain of Fear and served among her Imperial champions during the events of The White Rose.A former Annalist of the Black Company who helped write the Book of Kette with Straw, Agrip, and Holm during the Company's second century, while it served the Paingod of Cho'n Delor.A sworn brother of the Black Company from Taglios, mentioned briefly in She Is the Darkness. Murgen noted that the "Pete" part of his nickname derived from the center syllable of a lengthy Gunni godname, and he was referred to in full to distinguish him from Khusavir Pete. He was one of Big Bucket's favored subordinates, overseeing a work party assigned to transport water.A sworn brother of the Black Company likely originating from Hsien, based on his name. He served as a combatant during the Protectorate war in Soldiers Live.The second-in-command of the Black Company during the earliest chronicles, known by no other name. A former cabin boy turned military engineer with a particular expertise in siege weapons, he was already an experienced soldier and tactician by the time he joined the Company. A staunch traditionalist who rarely fraternized with the other brothers, Croaker knew him as a notoriously poor tonk player with a sour disposition and an unexpectedly dry sense of humor.The most evil and violent of the Ten Who Were Taken, originally an independent wizard-king before the Dominator enslaved him. Short, dressed in ragged brown robes, he wore an old leather mask over a mummified face — patches of rotting flesh, exposed gums and teeth on the right side. A prominent scar from forehead to left cheek was reportedly inflicted by the White Rose herself. His trademark limp is of unknown origin. The most sadistic of the Taken, his armies were ill-disciplined and his governance of the port city of Opal was defined by lawlessness and bloody power grabs. An expert in destructive battlefield sorcery, he possessed a ferocious resilience to harm and was an accomplished pilot of flying carpets.A man-eating supernatural monster summoned by the Limper during a violent confrontation with the Prince of Meadenvil's guard in Shadows Linger. Its ultimate fate is not recorded in the Annals.A sorcerer and member of the Circle of Eighteen, the Rebel leadership warring against the Lady's Empire, mentioned during The Black Company. He led a significant Rebel force and joined Harden's larger army at the Stair of Tear.An impoverished young woman from the Buskin, the slums of the city of Juniper, who briefly crossed paths with the Black Company as a barmaid at the Iron Lily tavern in Shadows Linger. She worked for the tavern's owner, Marron Shed, after he took her in to protect her from her abusive father.One of three brothers, alongside Cletus and Longinus, natives of the Jewel City of Beryl who joined the Black Company in Shadow Games. Formerly of Beryl's Urban Cohorts, the three quickly established themselves as indispensable military engineers, artillery specialists, and architects within the Company.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in the Annals of the first chronicle. Before serving in the Lady's Empire, he had been with the Company in Beryl and crossed the Sea of Torments aboard Soulcatcher's giant galley, The Dark Wings, to Opal.One of three brothers, alongside Cletus and Loftus, natives of the Jewel City of Beryl who joined the Black Company in Shadow Games. Formerly of Beryl's Urban Cohorts, the three quickly established themselves as indispensable military engineers, artillery specialists, and architects within the Company.A reviled sorcerer dwelling in the extreme south of the homeworld, founder of the Shadowmasters, and chief enemy of the Black Company and Taglios. Tall, thin, gaunt, and visibly unwell, he was prone to rage and violent shaking spells. His floor-length black robe was threaded with silver, gold, and glistening black protections, reflecting both his formidable magic and deeply fearful nature.A major city of the Lady's Empire, east of the Forest of Cloud and west of the Plain of Fear, connected by road to the Salient. Governed by Nightcrawler of the Ten Who Were Taken, it became a focus of Rebel activity and Imperial countermeasures. The Black Company later quartered there during the northern war.A Colonel who commanded the mercenary group Drake Crest from the city of Roses, mentioned briefly in The White Rose.A sworn brother of the Black Company whose birth name was Tam Do Linh. One of the Children of the Dead from Hsien, he enlisted during the Company's four years of rebuilding and recruitment at the Abode of Ravens. He appears in Soldiers Live as a combatant among the brotherhood's Hsien-born soldiers.The patriarch of the Senjak family, a prominent ruling-class house during the Domination, and husband of Banat Senjak. A mysterious figure about whom little is recorded, he was the father of four daughters celebrated as rivals in loveliness. Unlike the ethnic group favored by the Dominator, Lunwen was not TelleKurre.The barkeeper of a tavern in the eastern kingdom of Tally, whose establishment became entangled in the conflict between the Black Company, serving the Lady's Empire, and the local Rebel movement during Shadows Linger.A young man from the ruling family of the Voroshk world, nephew of the patriarch known as the First Father, who appears in Soldiers Live. He had a strained relationship with his own father, who in turn resented his brother, the First Father. Croaker noted that Magadan possessed a natural healer's touch.The most famous saint in the long history of the Stranglers cult, a murky figure from the distant past of the homeworld who lived centuries before the arrival of the first Free Companies of Khatovar. His most celebrated deed was the killing of Rhaydreynak, the ancient emperor of what would become Taglios and the Shadowlands, who had persecuted the Stranglers to near extinction. He was the only cultist in the sect's history honored with a silver rumel, a mark reserved for those who killed at least a thousand people, and modern Stranglers such as Narayan Singh revere him as a legendary figure.Airborne creatures native to the Plain of Fear, mantas physically resemble the rays of tropical seas and spend most of their lives in flight. Adults have wingspans of thirty to fifty feet and can produce dangerous electrical bolts to stun enemies or prey. Their colonies live in close symbiosis with windwhales: young mantas, called kits, are born in crevices on the great beasts' backs and remain there until capable of independent flight.The owner of the Dark Horse tavern in the republic of Aloe throughout Port of Shadows. His establishment became a favorite haunt of the Black Company while it was garrisoned in the city, placing him in regular contact with its veteran soldiers. A local family man, Markeg had a wife, a daughter named Sora Zhorab, and an unnamed sister.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned during their garrison in the city of Aloe in Port of Shadows. He was part of a pioneer squad tasked by the Captain with a minor supply errand.The owner of the Iron Lily bar and inn in the Buskin, the poorest section of the city of Juniper, whose experiences form a significant part of the chronicles of Shadows Linger. Though well known locally for his cowardice, he could show real kindness, notably toward a homeless man named Asa, whom he allowed to sleep by the fire in exchange for firewood. He lived at the Lily together with his blind, arthritic mother, June, and became entangled in the affairs of the Black Company after the former brother Raven and his ward Darling came to stay at his inn.An ancient, immortal, and immensely powerful sorcerer who operated in secrecy on the northern continent from before the Domination into Croaker's lifetime. Hidden in a castle near the Rip, he had become immobile through centuries of gluttony. One of the few sorcerers capable of the Rite of Taking, he commanded several enslaved wizards, including Blind Emon.A white man from the southern continent, sworn brother of the Black Company, and one of its sergeants during the first chronicle. He belonged to the experienced noncommissioned leadership supporting the Captain during the Company's early northern service. Little personal history beyond his rank and allegiance is recorded.A major port city and independent principality on the western ocean in the northwestern reaches of the northern continent, south of Juniper and the Wolander Mountains and north of Shaker. An unwalled harbor governed by its own prince, it participated in maritime trade through the Gap and Strait of Vermust toward the Jewel Cities and other ports. Its residents regarded Juniper and that city's zealous cult of the dead as backward, while Croaker found Meadenvil fresh, lively, and refreshing by comparison.Known in the Annals only as "the fat man," the owner of a countryside inn outside the city of Meadenvil in Shadows Linger. He and his family ran a modestly prosperous establishment, and he became entangled in the affairs of the Black Company after members of the group passed through the area.An antiquities digger active in the Barrowland during the lifetime of Bomanz. He was Bomanz's primary competitor for artifacts at the ancient site, placing the two men in a sustained professional rivalry. His role belongs to the earlier Barrowland narrative recounted in The White Rose.Intelligent, towering, rectangular stones native to the Plain of Fear, created by the god Father Tree and counted among the principal allies of Darling and her New White Rose Rebellion. Grey-brown, moss-covered, and capable of growing over time, they move by instantly and silently teleporting from place to place, a feat they rarely perform while being observed by humans, and they retain their intelligence and mobility even within Darling's anti-magic null field. Their dry, acerbic manner of speech and unsettling laughter unnerved even their closest human allies.A prominent sergeant in the Black Company active before and during the opening events of the first chronicle in Beryl. Croaker described him as a smallish, cocky man fond of dramatic gestures, with a booming voice and a notably vicious, cutthroat reputation even among his fellow Company brothers.Supernatural, shape-shifting women encountered by the Black Company in the short story Wet Dream Fish Story, part of the On The Long Run arc. They inhabited the rivers surrounding an ancient, man-made island in the western wilderness, appearing partially submerged with teeth resembling a cross between a lamprey and a sand shark, and communicating in clicks, snorts, and whistles. They existed in long-standing tension with a trio of immortal mermaid-hunters marooned on the same island, though the mermaids themselves proved to be neither clear allies nor enemies of the Company.The young personal assistant of Sleepy, Captain of the Black Company, during Soldiers Live. About sixteen years old, charming, and well liked for his winning personality, he was illiterate but a skilled rider of the rheitgeistiden, the flying posts supplied by the Voroshk.An Annalist of the Black Company and one of Croaker's predecessors in that role, alongside Kanwas Scar. Their tenures were notoriously lax, leaving relatively little from that era of Company history preserved in the Annals beyond what later Annalists reconstructed from oral tradition and survivors' memories.A sworn brother of the Black Company from Hsien who appeared in Soldiers Live, notably younger than his fellow soldier Runmust Singh. Having previously served under the warlords of Hsien, he was selected as a ranger for the Company due to his combat experience and his ready acceptance of Company doctrine.A sworn brother of the Black Company who served as Croaker's understudy physician for part of Port of Shadows. Croaker described him bluntly as "mostly a waste of air," and he was tasked, alongside Corey, with keeping watch over Buzz after the discovery of the otherworldly chinkami in Aloe.A strange and powerful Imperial sorceress in Port of Shadows, believed to be one of the new Taken. Arriving in Aloe with authority over senior Imperials, she was marked by moving tattoos, a star-patterned black yukata, and an ornate flying carpet. Her retinue included the mysterious twins Baku and Shin and the three-eyed cat Ankou.A soldier of the Black Company mentioned in Port of Shadows. The Annals associate the cryptic phrase "Worn weak with lack of wonder" with his name but preserve no explanation for it. Nothing else about his origins, appearance, or service is recorded.The acclaimed leader of the thirty-three Nar warriors who joined the Black Company in Shadow Games. A member of Gea-Xle's elite warrior caste and a descendant of the Company's old priestly line, he was renowned as the strongest and most skilled of the Nar. Croaker considered him one of the finest soldiers he had known, and he commanded Company infantry while training the Taglian First Legion.A hunter from the hinterland east of Meadenvil during Shadows Linger. He was well known to a country innkeeper outside the city and usually visited in autumn to purchase staples for the approaching winter. The innkeeper noted that Moleskin bore a physical resemblance to Raven, but little else about the hunter's appearance or personality is recorded.An influential jamadar, or band leader, within the secret Stranglers cult, appearing in Dreams of Steel. A black rumel man of Vehdna background, his reputation within the cult nearly rivaled that of Narayan Singh, the most influential black rumel man alive.One of the Ten Who Were Taken, the group of powerful sorcerers compelled to serve the Dominator during the Domination. Croaker never encountered Moonbiter personally, leaving almost no individual description or account of her magic in the Annals. The surviving references suggest, without stating conclusively, that Moonbiter was likely one of the women among the Ten.A high-magnitude sorcerer and one of the four Shadowmasters, and the companion of Stormshadow. Unlike Stormshadow, he was not one of the Ten Who Were Taken, and unlike Longshadow and Shadowspinner, he was native to the homeworld rather than an outsider. Relatively little else is recorded about his origins in the Annals.The wife of Raven and mother of his twin children, born into an aristocratic family of the Jewel City of Opal. She was placed into an arranged, loveless marriage with the young Baronet Corvo, an aristocrat with significant properties and titles, and left the care of their children largely to nurses.A sorcerer and member of the Circle of Eighteen, leading a significant Rebel force warring against the Imperial armies of the Lady and her generals, the Ten Who Were Taken. Moth fought alongside fellow Circle member Sidle on the Plain of Fear, and later joined forces with Circle member Linger as part of Harden's massive army at the Stair of Tear. Soulcatcher considered Moth central to the strength of the Rebel cause.One of a hundred young Taglian men who reported to the Company wizard Goblin during his Shaded Road commando operation in She Is the Darkness, hoping to join the Black Company. Goblin had presented the mission to the aspirants as a kind of entrance exam.An introspective and taciturn brother of the Black Company who served as its Standardbearer. More than six feet tall, lean, and seemingly permanently sad, he carried and protected the Company's ancient banner on the Lance of Passion. His reserved temperament and solemn responsibility made him a distinctive younger member of the brotherhood.A Nyueng Bao woman, wife of the swordsman Thai Dei, and mother of their son, To Tan. Her place within that family connects her to Ky Sahra, Thai Dei's sister, and to the wider Nyueng Bao community encountered by the Black Company. The Annals record little else about her personality or background.A wizard of significant magnitude, mentioned in events that took place before The Black Company. In D'loc Aloc, he took on the young One-Eye and Tom-Tom as apprentices, and later attempted to destroy a young male forvalaka, losing an arm and a foot in the failed attempt.The most influential Strangler jamadar of the modern Annals, devoted to the goddess Kina. Gunni by birth despite his Shadar-sounding name, he had been a vegetable peddler in Gondowar before dedicating himself to the cult. As leader of the secret Changlor band, he commanded absolute loyalty even from followers who publicly outranked him by caste.A young Taglian officer serving under Great General Mogaba during the Protectorate war depicted in Soldiers Live. The heir of an aristocratic family that had served Taglios at arms for three generations, dating back to the earliest skirmishes of the Shadowmaster wars, Saraswati held the post of regimental chief of staff and was noted by Mogaba for his aggressive attitude, in contrast to more timid subordinates.A prince of the ruling family of the Voroshk world who appears in Soldiers Live. He was the brother of the family patriarch known as the First Father and the father of Gromovol, placing him near the center of Voroshk dynastic life. Croaker regarded Nashun as reclusive and cowardly, despite the status suggested by his title and lineage.A wizard active among the freelance spike hunters seeking the silver spike in the besieged city of Oar, during The Silver Spike. He and four hired thugs rented rooms in the downtrodden North Side of the city, near the Skull and Crossbones tavern, while awaiting information or an opportunity to locate the talisman.A mid-level leader of the local Rebel movement opposing the Lady's Empire in the eastern province of Tally, mentioned in Shadows Linger. His resistance activities were limited mostly to ambushing occasional Imperial couriers.The prehistoric creators of the glittering plain, possessed of wizardry on a godlike scale, whose sorcery linked sixteen different worlds together via overland routes crossing the plain. The name is also used for three lesser spectral entities, the Washane, the Washene, and the Washone, brought into being by the lonely golem Shivetya as companions modeled after the vanished original Nef. Both the original Nef and their descendants are described as strikingly hideous, with heads and one side of the body obscured by masks resembling polished brass fish scales.One of the Ten Who Were Taken, the powerful sorcerers who served the Dominator during the Domination and later the Lady's Empire. Like Moonbiter and the Faceless Man, Croaker never encountered him personally, so little is recorded of his appearance or specific abilities beyond his sigil, a snake. He commanded the defense of the major Imperial city of Lords and later led forces that recaptured the eastern Rebel city of Thud.A large, crowded, walled city in the far north of the Lady's Empire, just south of the Great Forest and north of the fortress at Deal. Once the capital of the independent kingdom of Forsberg, it became the province's capital after the Lady's consolidation wars and remained the last major city in the central northern continent. Oar used the obol as currency, monopolized the Barrowland settlement's fur trade, and contained landmarks ranging from the Black Campus and Mayfield Square to the notorious North Side slum.One of the thirty-three Nar warriors from Gea-Xle who joined the Black Company in Shadow Games alongside their leader Mogaba. He rose to become one of Croaker's most trusted generals during the Shadowmaster wars, serving as a general in the Prahbrindrah Drah's Taglian army while answering directly to Lady, the Company's Lieutenant.The leader of the ruling family of the Voroshk world, mentioned in Soldiers Live. A mysterious figure who reigned for many years, he was the predecessor of his successor, the First Father, and several other Voroshk relatives who would later play roles in the affairs of the Black Company.A wrinkled little man appearing in Dreams of Steel who was impressively articulate, fluent in Taglian, and a master of negotiation. His unwieldy chosen designation reflected a modest view of himself as a servant or pawn rather than an independent power. The title also marked him as the leader of a small group of subordinates.A long-lived Black Company wizard recognizable by his filthy black hat and notorious for drinking, gambling, and crime. His elaborate feud with Goblin concealed a deep friendship. Though a minor sorcerer, his illusions were valuable in battle, and he served as Croaker's principal assistant in battlefield surgery.A major harbor city on the southern coast of the northern continent, overlooking the Sea of Torments. A member of the famous Jewel Cities and the only one located outside the southern continent, it is at least two centuries old but younger than Beryl, their ancient queen. Opal serves as a transit hub for sea travelers, speaks the Jewel Cities dialect, and is known for the Gardens, an exclusive establishment serving refined patrons for two hundred years.A soldier of the Black Company mentioned in Port of Shadows. The Annals associate the cryptic phrase "The proud do not endure" with his name but offer no explanation for it. Nothing else about his origins, appearance, or service is recorded.A veteran from Rebosa on the southern continent and one of the Black Company's longest-serving brothers. Usually found alongside his close companion Hagop, he had a polytheistic upbringing and sometimes carried a large ax into combat. Croaker described Otto as possessing very little conscience while still considering him a proficient and reliable soldier.The Black Company's dedicated grave keeper during their garrison in Aloe in Port of Shadows, responsible for burying fallen Company members and composing the inscriptions on their memorial stones. The Company arranged with the owner of a nearby apple orchard to allow him to bury the dead there during their stay, and Croaker recorded seventeen of his epitaphs in the Annals.One of the three Torque brothers, alongside Stubby and Brother Bear, and a sworn member of the Black Company. The brothers came from the eastern region of the Lady's Empire, reported to the Lieutenant and Elmo, and remained loyal to Darling, whom they followed after the Battle of the Barrowland.A sorcerer of high magnitude who ruled as tyrant over Cho'n Delor on the southern continent two centuries before Croaker's Books of the North. One of the earliest employers remembered in Black Company history, he hired the brotherhood during the Pastel Wars against the rival Triplet Cities. At that time the Company was an immense force numbering more than six thousand soldiers.A tribune from Taglios mentioned in Bleak Seasons, loyal to the Taglian prince, the Prahbrindrah Drah. During the Siege of Dejagore, he aligned himself with Mogaba, one of the Black Company's rival faction leaders within the besieged city.A member of the Black Company originating from Hsien and one of the Children of the Dead. His Company nickname came from its resemblance to his otherwise unrecorded real name. He appears in Soldiers Live among the Hsien-born soldiers of the reconstituted mercenary brotherhood.The nickname of a mysterious and highly skilled necromancer who lived in Dusk, the Domination's capital, during the late Domination era. Obsessed with restoring life after death, he practiced his forbidden sorcery in secret, and his experiments and hidden refuge in the distant Ghost Country become central to one of the mysteries explored in Port of Shadows.A sorcerer and member of the Circle of Eighteen, the Rebel leadership opposing the Lady's Empire during The Black Company. As one of the Circle's commanders, he led a significant Rebel force against Imperial armies and the Ten Who Were Taken. Little individual detail about his appearance or magic is preserved.A series of major conflicts near the Second Cataract of the southern continent's great river, about two hundred years before The Black Company. Cho'n Delor, ruled by the Paingod and defended by the Black Company, fought the Triplet Cities. The Triplet Cities prevailed, but both sides were reduced to ruins and the region became scarred and haunted. The wars were remembered for pastel ribbons of battlefield sorcery and for the loss of four successive Annalists and the early Annals.A sworn brother of the Black Company and a skilled roi nomad horseman mentioned in Shadow Games. Originally a caravan guard operating south of Ha-jah, he deserted his people alongside three other roi, including Shadid, to join the Free Company.A sworn brother and respected veteran of the Black Company, born on the southern continent. Known as Pawn for short, he disliked the moniker Pawnbroker but preferred it to his birth name, Sugar Beet. He lent money to fellow Company members and was trusted to accompany senior veterans on dangerous assignments.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in the Annals of the first chronicle. Present during the band's service to the Syndic of Beryl, he crossed the Sea of Torments aboard Soulcatcher's giant galley, The Dark Wings, to Opal.A sworn brother of the Black Company from Hsien, mentioned in Soldiers Live. He served as a combatant during the Protectorate war.A member of the Nyueng Bao De Duang people and a disciple of Uncle Doj's Path of the Sword tradition. After the Siege of Dejagore, he became one of the unofficial bodyguards assigned to protect members of the Black Company's Old Crew, out of gratitude for their role in saving the surviving Nyueng Bao population.A regional warlord of Hsien from the territory of Ghu Phi, and the senior-most member of the File of Nine council during Soldiers Live. Croaker considered him an excellent general with a good reputation among his troops and a believer in a unified Hsien, in contrast to some of his more disreputable colleagues on the File.The quartermaster of the Black Company prior to the events in Beryl and throughout the first chronicle, responsible for maintaining supplies and equipment. Known as a skilled tonk player because of his talent for bluffing, he got along well with both Raven and the elderly Forsberger Flick, from whom he enjoyed collecting superstitious stories.A bizarre desert in the eastern portion of the northern continent, the Plain of Fear is home to over forty unique and intelligent species found nowhere else: windwhales, flying mantas, reversed centaurs, talking buzzards, and enigmatic talking stones called menhirs, among others. The Plain is also notorious for supernatural "change storms" that can transform any living thing caught in them. At its heart resides Father Tree, an alien entity worshiped by the Plain's creatures and the rare wild human tribes as their god, who serves as its ultimate protector and ruler.A relatively young member of the Black Company who became a trainee physician under Croaker's guidance, appearing in Shadows Linger. Under the Captain's orders, he established a field hospital in the impoverished Buskin neighborhood of Juniper to build goodwill among the local population.A white man from the southern continent and sworn brother of the Black Company in the first chronicle. He served with the band during its contract with the Syndic of Beryl and is also mentioned during its subsequent employment in the Lady's Empire. The page preserves no further safe detail about his origins or personality.A sworn brother of the underground Black Company during Water Sleeps, described as "barely competent." Embedded among the population of Taglios, he worked alongside Spiff as a courier and sentry under the wizard One-Eye, ultimately answering to the Company's ranking officer, Sleepy.A sergeant of the Black Company mentioned in Port of Shadows. The Annals associate the energetic phrase "Getting on with the ass-kicking" with his name but provide no context for it. His rank is the only other personal detail preserved.The Prince of Taglios and its formal ruler during the modern Annals, though in practice much of the city's real power was exercised by his younger sister, the Radisha Drah, and shared with the high priests of the Gunni, Shadar, and Vehdna cults. He and the Radisha resided in the Palace of Taglios, and Croaker noted that, unusually for a Taglian aristocrat, he handled a sword well. His contract with the Black Company shaped many of the major events of the Books of the South.Often shortened to Precious, a sorcerer and the son of Laissa and the necromancer Papa, born and raised in his father's hidden granite castle deep within the shunned Ghost Country. He continues his father's research into necromancy and the creation of life, presiding over the strange, isolated community there.The ruler of Meadenvil, an independent and unwalled harbor city in the northwest of the northern continent, mentioned in Shadows Linger. Protective of his sovereignty and supported by a city guard, he expected powerful foreign visitors to respect his authority. No personal name, appearance, or family history is recorded for him.Also known as the Woman, the influential sister of the Prince of Taglios, the Prahbrindrah Drah. Because Taglios's strict caste system barred women from exercising power overtly, she worked politically in the shadows while her brother received the public credit and blame for her decisions. Widely respected for her sharp wit and fierce intelligence, she worked closely in her early years with the court wizard Smoke as one of her primary sources of political intelligence.An older male sorcerer and one of the most prominent and successful members of the Circle of Eighteen, the Rebel leadership warring against the Lady's Empire. Raker was known for a series of victories against the Limper, one of the Lady's Ten Who Were Taken, in the northern province of Forsberg, and for a bitter rivalry with his brother-in-law and fellow Circle member, Harden.A twenty-three-year-old carter from Taglios in Dreams of Steel. Tall, massive, muscular, and notably hairy, he had spent his life in the city and knew little of the surrounding countryside. His urban background and imposing build made him a memorable but inexperienced traveler beyond Taglios.A sworn brother of the underground Black Company mentioned briefly in Water Sleeps. Like other members of the Company at the time, he worked a day job as a laborer for their Nyueng Bao collaborator Banh Do Trang while handling Company affairs during off-hours.A Taglian ambassador mentioned briefly in Bleak Seasons alongside his fellow envoy Chal Ghanda Ghan. The pair represented Taglios and played a political role during the Siege of Dejagore. His recorded importance is diplomatic rather than military, with little personal detail preserved.The Black Company's first recruit after its crossing of the Sea of Torments, Raven was a reserved young aristocrat from Opal with some training in sorcery. Thin, dark-haired, dusky-skinned, and not especially tall, he excelled with knives, archery, and tracking. His exceptional combat ability, cold-blooded manner, and refusal to discuss his past made him feared by friends and enemies alike.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned once in the Annals, during the Company's garrison in Aloe in Port of Shadows. He and Tuco assisted the wizard Silent in a mission for the Company, having apparently enlisted sometime before the group's arrival in the region.The collective term for forces opposing the Lady's Empire on the northern continent, led chiefly by the powerful sorcerers of the Circle of Eighteen. Their cause drew strength from prophecies concerning the Great Comet and the return of the White Rose. They fought sustained campaigns against Imperial armies, the Ten Who Were Taken, and mercenaries including the Black Company.A thug working for the gangster Krage in the Buskin, the most downtrodden slum of the city of Juniper, during Shadows Linger. Missing at least three teeth, he was known to torment Krage's victims for amusement, and took part in confronting and attempting to extort money from the tavernkeeper Marron Shed.A white man from Opal who joined the Black Company alongside his longtime friend Big Bucket, Sparkle, and Candles. Their enlistment expanded the greatly reduced brotherhood during its passage through the northern continent. Rudy traveled with the small group aboard the immense Imperial flagship The Dark Wings on the journey across the Sea of Torments.A Rebel field major mentioned in The Black Company, serving as chief-of-staff to Harden, one of the most powerful and prominent sorcerer-generals of the Circle of Eighteen. Reef was known to travel with Harden in the province of Forsberg, alongside Harden's nephew, Motrin Hanin.An ancient warlord and emperor mentioned in Dreams of Steel and several of the Books of Glittering Stone, who ruled a mighty empire on the southern continent, in what is now Taglios, ages before the arrival of the Free Companies of Khatovar. He persecuted the followers of the goddess Kina, the Stranglers cult, driving them from his empire and forcing them to hide their sacred Books of the Dead within Shivetya's fortress at the center of the glittering plain. Narayan Singh, the greatest Strangler jamadar of the modern Annals, related Rhaydreynak's story to Lady.A master sergeant of the Black Company and one of Sleepy's most trusted officers and advisors by the time of Water Sleeps, and a veteran of the Kiaulune wars. A Gunni presumably from Taglios, he was known to Sleepy only by this single name, an occurrence not uncommon in Company history. Unlike fellow sergeant Slink, Riverwalker had little skill for stealth. During the Company's underground years in Taglios, he worked a day job to maintain his cover while handling Company affairs after hours, and carried out a number of covert abductions on Sleepy's orders.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned briefly in Water Sleeps, who accompanied Sleepy and her Nyueng Bao allies on their first journey across the glittering plain. Along with Willow Swan and Riverwalker, he was among those who slept close enough to Sleepy to experience her notoriously loud snoring.A sworn brother of the Black Company during the short stories "Shaggy Dog Bridge" and "Bone Eaters," and mentioned in "Chasing Midnight: The Dark Lord as a Teen." The only friend of the newcomer Rusty, and simultaneously his favorite target, Robin's origins are unspecified, though his closeness to Rusty suggests he may hail from the same city of Chimney. During the Company's time in the western wilderness, he served on a reconnaissance team led by Elmo alongside Rusty, Whittle, the archer Zeb, the wizard One-Eye, and the Annalist Croaker, helping investigate a mysterious, centuries-old bridge hidden by sorcery.A sorcerer and member of the Circle of Eighteen, and the leader of a significant Rebel force warring against the Imperial armies of the Lady and her generals, the Ten Who Were Taken, leading up to and during the events of The Black Company. Roper commanded a portion of the quarter-million Rebels besieging the Tower at Charm during the war's climactic battle.A major walled city in the central part of the Lady's Empire, enclaved within the Salient province. Despite lying within firmly Imperial territory, Roses holds the unique distinction of being a free republic with its own independent sovereignty. Its walls are painted pale red, three rivers course through it connected by a web of canals, and its numerous arched bridges are among the city's most celebrated features. The Rosean language originated here. A road to the south connects Roses to Meystrikt, the most important fortress of the Salient.A master sergeant of the Black Company by the time of Sleepy's leadership of the underground movement in Taglios. He and his slightly smaller brother Iqbal, both veterans of the Kiaulune wars, were among Sleepy's key operatives during Water Sleeps and Soldiers Live. The two brothers were imposing, hirsute men of the Shadar ethno-religious group; despite their shared surname, they were unrelated to the Company's notorious enemy Narayan Singh, since Singh was one of the most common Shadar surnames in overpopulated Taglios.One of five huge and formidable cities forming an arc east of the Plain of Fear in the northern continent, alongside Frost, Thud, Ade, and Barns. Rust was the focus of numerous protracted and bloody Rebel uprisings against the Lady's Empire. The fighting around Rust was described as particularly bitter and sustained, with both sides driven to extreme measures during prolonged sieges. The city was also notable for its "amazon regiments": Rebel formations composed entirely of women.A sworn brother of the Black Company from Chimney who appears across several of the short stories collected in On The Long Run, including "Those Who Went Before," "Shaggy Dog Bridge," "Bone Eaters," and "Chasing Midnight: The Dark Lord as a Teen." Known for selfish and aggressive behavior that drew deep disapproval from Croaker the Annalist and most of his fellow soldiers, he was nonetheless defended by his only friend, the newcomer Robin. Rusty joined the Company at his birthplace of Chimney before its final embarkation aboard the ship Cranky Bitch, and later marched with the band into the western wilderness.A noteworthy town or city in the northern portion of the Lady's Empire, besieged by the Rebel. Its precise location is not fully given in the Annals, though context places it south of the Salient and west of Lords, in a region associated with Elm, Wist, Jane, and Wine. One of the most effective of the Ten Who Were Taken, Shapeshifter, was dispatched there to hold the city against the Rebel siege.A long, arrowhead-shaped province of flatland pointing south between mountain ranges in the northern continent. Its most important city is Roses, a free republican enclave, and its most important fortress is Meystrikt. Forsberg lies to the north, the Forest of Cloud to the east, and a long road links the Salient to the major city of Lords. Presumed one of the earliest provinces absorbed into the Lady's Empire, given its proximity to the Tower at Charm.A Voroshk woman mentioned briefly in Soldiers Live. The First Father, the Family's chief patriarch, put aside Shukrat's mother and took Saltireva as his lover, an affair that deeply and permanently hurt Shukrat. The episode was recounted by Arkana to Magadan.A member of the Nyueng Bao De Duang people and the first husband of Ky Sahra. He was hastily chosen as her husband by her mother, Ky Gota, largely for his apparent wealth, though he had in fact been disinherited by his own family for cruelty, wickedness, and treachery, a fact Gota failed to investigate. Danh proved a brutal husband even after fathering Sahra's first two children. Sleepy later wrote in her Annals that "no one who remembered the man spoke well of him."The sole offspring of Father Tree, the ancient entity at the heart of the Plain of Fear. Created during The White Rose, it already possessed considerable height from the moment it was brought into being. As the only known descendant of that godlike tree, the Sapling carried unusual importance among the creatures of the Plain.Also called Scarstone, one of the menhirs, the intelligent talking stones native to the Plain of Fear, who often served as their spokesman in The Silver Spike. Like all menhirs, his loyalty to his creator, Father Tree, was unwavering. He received his nickname from the Eternal Guard soldier Case, on account of a distinctive scar running down one side of his face. Communicating with the deaf-mute Darling through Silent's finger speech, Scar helped persuade the despondent wizard Bomanz that he was needed in the fight against the Limper and Toadkiller Dog.One of the new Taken, a group of eight powerful sorcerers bound to the Lady through the Rite of Taking, whose members dressed identically and were difficult to tell apart; Croaker was never able to determine whether Scorn was male or female. Scorn was stationed at the town of Hull during the Lady's encirclement of the Plain of Fear and served among her Imperial champions during the events of The White Rose.A young man from the ruling family of the Voroshk world who appears in Soldiers Live. The eldest among a group of four Voroshk teenagers that also included Gromovol, Magadan, and Arkana, he had been raised to expect the privileges of royalty. Croaker regarded Sedvod as the most truculent of the young nobles.The owner of a tavern called the Ruby Glass in the city of Meadenvil, who appeared briefly in Shadows Linger. Selkirk held a business meeting at his tavern with the fugitive Marron Shed, formerly of the Iron Lily in Juniper's Buskin district, who hoped to start a new life and business partnership in Meadenvil. During their meeting, Selkirk mentioned a recent string of unexplained nighttime disappearances in the city.A high priest in Taglios during the events of Soldiers Live. Toward the end of the Protectorate, he held the influential title of Purohita and a seat on the Privy Council, before Soulcatcher ordered Great General Mogaba to remove him from the position over his disapproving attitude, including opposition to her plan to harvest timber from the Grove of Doom.A sworn brother of the Black Company and a roi nomad who appeared in Shadow Games, known for the horsemanship typical of his people. Alongside three other roi, he deserted his caravan-guard livelihood to join the Company, and after reaching Taglios he helped train the newly formed Taglian cavalry, earning one of the Company's prized black stallions as his mount.The malevolent, immortal spirits that have haunted the glittering plain for millennia, also called the Host of the Unforgiven Dead in the Land of Unknown Shadows and skildirsha in the Shadowlander language. Loathing all life, they attack at any opportunity, though only the largest among them can kill outright, and they can pass through the smallest of gaps. They are repelled only by light and by sorcery, which can also be used to control or destroy them, and the Shadowmasters and, later, Soulcatcher learned to tame smaller shadows as messengers and larger ones as assassins.A former sailor from the Juniperen ship Cranky Bitch who joined the Black Company by the time of the short story Wet Dream Fish Story. He earned his nickname for being so thin that he "didn't cast a shadow," and was known to the physician Croaker as a frequent victim of accidental injuries and wildlife bites during the Company's trek through the western wilderness.One of the four powerful sorcerers who established the Shadowlands in the far south of the homeworld, headquartered at the city called Shadowlight. Despite his advanced age, he appeared middle-aged, with blond hair and extremely pale skin, though he was not albino. Personable and intelligent in manner, he commanded shadows and wielded destructive magic strong enough to concern even Longshadow.A sergeant of the Black Company who took part in the Juniper campaign of Shadows Linger. During the Battle of Juniper, he and the wizard One-Eye directed a group of laborers digging a sapper's tunnel meant to undermine one of the walls of the black castle, making no attempt to conceal the effort since their demonic opponents, the castle creatures, would have seen through any subterfuge. When the castle creatures rushed out to attack the laborers, Shaky and One-Eye stood their ground while the Lieutenant ordered covering arrow fire to protect the men fleeing across the exposed slope.One of the immensely powerful sorcerers known as the Ten Who Were Taken, and a key enforcer of the Lady's Empire, also known simply as Shifter. An extraordinarily tall man with grey hair and a thick, unkempt beard covering most of his face, he wore heavily tattered scarlet clothing and carried a distinctive staff carved in the shape of an elongated female body. True to his name, he possessed the sorcerous ability to transform into other people, animals, and monstrous forms at will.A sworn brother of the Black Company active during the Juniper campaign of Shadows Linger. He was part of an advance team of twenty-five Company men flown ahead of the main body into the city by the new Taken via flying carpet, alongside the physician and Annalist Croaker, the wizard Goblin, and other trusted soldiers. Along with Tickle, Kingpin, and Pawnbroker, Sharkey was assigned to keep watch over Marron Shed, the owner of the Iron Lily tavern, under cover as a sailor who had missed his ship.A new recruit of the Black Company in the city of Aloe during the events of Port of Shadows. Unenthusiastic about the training ordered by the Captain, he preferred playing tonk with veterans like Goblin and Otto at the Dark Horse tavern. He correctly predicted an incoming seasonal storm for the sergeant Elmo, and later helped load a wagon for the physician Croaker.Also known as Beloved Shin, a mysterious young boy in service to the sorceress Mischievous Rain during the events of Port of Shadows, alongside his twin sister Baku and a cat-like creature named Ankou. Both children displayed intellect and sorcery well beyond their apparent age, including the ability to travel at supernatural speed through shadows. While the Black Company was stationed in Aloe, Shin crafted and distributed "shadow pots," earthenware jugs containing concentrated shadows that Company patrols could use to summon his aid against hostile forces.A sworn brother of the Black Company who held at least the rank of sergeant during She Is the Darkness. His seniority suggests that he probably came from Taglios rather than from the later Shadowlander recruits, though his precise origin is not recorded. He belonged to the same layer of Company leadership as Red Rudy, Big Bucket, Spiff, and Kloo.A giant, prehistoric, three-eyed, sentient golem at the center of the glittering plain. Created by the ancient Nef, he sat nailed to a wooden throne with silver knives inside a nameless fortress, burdened with maintaining the plain's machinery and guarding a deep subterranean prison. Though unable to leave his throne, he could communicate telepathically and possessed memories extending across millennia.Hired muscle for the wizard Abel, one of several freelance spike hunters competing to recover the silver spike in the besieged city of Oar during The Silver Spike. A very short man with a bellowing voice, he armed himself with a knife and brought two subordinate thugs, Smiley and Tanker, to help Abel in the search.A sworn brother of the Black Company who appeared across several short stories of the On The Long Run arc, also spelled Show Boy. Croaker the Annalist wrote that he "got his name because he talked a great game till it came time to play," later dubbing him the Company's "dimmest candle." He traveled with a small pet dog named Ralf, and during the Company's trek through the western wilderness he became entangled with a mermaid named Dai-Li, resurfacing days later confused and enchanted, unable to reliably recall what had truly happened to him.A young noblewoman from the ruling family of the Voroshk world and one of the first Voroshk encountered in Soldiers Live. Beautiful and in her mid-teens, she shared her people's pale skin, blonde hair, and blue eyes. Shukrat was notably sociable, direct, and less manipulative than her cousin Arkana, giving her an unusually open manner by both Voroshk and Black Company standards.A sorcerer and member of the Circle of Eighteen, leading a significant Rebel force warring against the Imperial armies of the Lady and her generals, the Ten Who Were Taken. Sidle fought alongside fellow Circle member Moth on the Plain of Fear, and later joined forces with Circle member Linger as part of Harden's massive army at the Stair of Tear. Soulcatcher considered Sidle central to the strength of the Rebel cause.A sworn brother and wizard of the Black Company who chose never to speak, though he was physically capable of doing so. He communicated through finger speech developed with Darling and formed a close companionship with her. A lower-magnitude wizard, he excelled at concealment, infiltration, controlling insects, and disabling enemies with noxious fumes; he was also a skilled swordsman and deeply valued the Company's records.A member of the Nar, the elite military caste of the city of Gea-Xle, who joined the Black Company alongside his lifelong friend and leader Mogaba and thirty-one other Nar in Shadow Games. He quickly became conversational in the Company's language, the Jewel Cities dialect, and was given command of an auxiliary Taglian legion when the Company entered the Shadowmaster wars. Murgen, who admired him above the other Nar, wrote that "of all the Nar, in those days, only Sindawe ever made the effort to be civil," noting his genuine effort to learn the Taglian language and understand Taglian culture.A muscular young man of Gunni descent who appeared in Dreams of Steel and the early Books of Glittering Stone. Tall, stocky, and exceptionally strong, Lady described him as a human stump built like a bear. His humorless personality and deeply sinister presence made him unsettling even beside the intimidating Narayan Singh.A hard-drinking sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in Port of Shadows, during the Company's garrison in Aloe in service to the Lady. He witnessed a flying carpet sneaking through the area east of Aloe, and though Croaker considered him "a huge drunk and hardly a reliable witness," his unexpected report was later verified and sparked intense discussion, since it indicated the presence of a mysterious, high-magnitude sorcerer unaligned with the Lady's Empire. Slapback reported the sighting to a young Aloen local, Gurdlief Speak, who relayed it to the Annalist Croaker.A young Vehdna Jaicuri who joined the Black Company at age fourteen with the sponsorship of Sergeant Big Bucket. Short, dark-skinned, and black-haired, she earned her nickname from a scar that made her left eyelid droop as though she were struggling to stay awake. She combined devotion to sacred texts with the hard pragmatism of a soldier, giving her a thoughtful but dangerous presence.A soldier of the Black Company mentioned in Port of Shadows, distinct from the Jaicuri member known as Sleepy. The Annals associate the cryptic phrase "Overcome with ugliness" with his name but do not explain it. No further background or service record is preserved.A sworn brother of the Black Company holding the rank of corporal in Water Sleeps. Jaicuri by birth and hailing from Dejagore, he was married, an observant Vehdna, and an avid tonk gambler with noticeably bad teeth. A sly and quietly loyal soldier, Slink conducted at least two major guerrilla operations on behalf of Sleepy and Ky Sahra during the Company's underground years in Taglios, and was likely a veteran of Sleepy's Kiaulune wars as well.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned briefly in Soldiers Live. He was part of Croaker's eclectic group of Company men and allies who entered the Voroshk world on a mission involving the shapeshifter Lisa Daele Bowalk, working alongside a roster that included Lady, Murgen, Thai Dei, Willow Swan, and Uncle Doj.A thief from Oar who appears in The Silver Spike. He operated as part of a four-man criminal group, though the available page records no safe introductory detail about his earlier life, appearance, or personality.A new recruit of the Black Company who enlisted in Shadow Games. A nephew of Hagop, he lived in the southern city of Rebosa before joining the greatly reduced Company as they passed through on their journey toward fabled Khatovar. He earned his ironic nickname for his consistent sullenness and sarcastic turn of phrase, and Croaker later noted that Smiley proved largely unhelpful in his duties.Hired muscle for the wizard Abel, one of several freelance spike hunters competing to recover the silver spike in the besieged city of Oar during The Silver Spike, alongside his companions Shorts and Tanker.A high adviser to the royal family of Taglios, publicly recognized as Lord of the Guardians of Public Safety and head of the city's fire brigade. Short and immediately recognizable by prominent light discolorations on dark skin, he was widely known for cowardice. His unrivaled knowledge of every room, hall, stairway, and entrance in the sprawling Palace made him indispensable at court.A powerful supernatural entity appearing in Shadow Games and associated with the wizard Goblin. It resembled a black snake formed from smoke, billowing from a pouch when manifested. Dangerous and difficult to understand, the creature represented an unseen threat within the Black Company's surroundings.A sworn brother of the Black Company during the short story "Shaggy Dog Bridge," part of the On The Long Run arc. He was part of a seven-man horseback patrol in the western wilderness with a spare horse, which picked up Croaker after he had been fleeing on foot to avoid detection by the sorceress Blind Emon.The very young sister of the Resurrectionists Tokar, Glory, and Clete, who appeared in the "flashback" narrative of the wizard Bomanz in The White Rose. Snoopy established a reputation in her home city of Oar for spying on her older siblings, though her age meant she was considered too young to be trusted with the details of their secretive mission.The knowledgeable, full-time librarian of the prosperous city of Aloe, who could read the sacred texts of the Aloen temple of Occupoa and became one of Croaker's main sources for information on ancient records. Publicly, she cultivated a reputation as a devout, unmarried woman who had dedicated her life to celibacy and scholarship.A prominent member of the Ten Who Were Taken and one of the Dominator's most powerful servants during the Domination. Centuries later, she commissioned the Black Company into the Lady's service and ferried it across the Sea of Torments. A short, slim sorceress in black armor and a featureless morion helm, she was famous for speaking in many different voices, earning the Nyueng Bao name Thousand Voices.A ferocious supernatural beast briefly summoned by Soulcatcher in Dreams of Steel. Huge, ugly, hungry, and faster than fleeing men, it emerged by tearing wider a magical opening in the fabric of the world. Steel left no mark on its snout, while its snarls were chilling enough to terrify nearby soldiers.A frightening supernatural entity appearing in Dreams of Steel. It could assume the form of dense smoke and pass through openings as small as a pinhole. When visible, it had a hideous, fanged face filled with grim purpose and left behind a distinctive odor resembling cinnamon, mustard, and wine mixed together.A fifteen-year-old brother of the Black Company who featured prominently in the short story "Those Who Went Before," part of the On The Long Run arc. One of the young recruits from Chimney, he was intended, along with Butterbutt, to serve as an apprentice to the physician Croaker, and despite shirking much of his training, Croaker considered him his leading apprentice and "one of the smartest Chimney kids." During the Company's passage through the sorcery-charged Grand Memorial to Our Honored Dead, Spangler was among several newcomers incapacitated after touching one of the cemetery's memorial posts.A member of the Black Company from Opal, accepted into the ranks alongside Big Bucket, Red Rudy, and Candles in Shadow Games. He earned his nickname from One-Eye and Goblin on account of his gold-inlaid front teeth. Sparkle crossed the Sea of Torments aboard the imperial flagship The Dark Wings, and later served in the Company's Old Crew faction during the Siege of Dejagore, continually shadowed afterward by a loyal Nyueng Bao Path of the Sword bodyguard.An influential sorceress in the Lady's Empire during The Silver Spike. She and her twin sister, Gossamer, trained in the art of magic at the Tower at Charm and dressed in black in imitation of the Ten Who Were Taken. She was sent to the besieged city of Oar with the Nightstalker Brigade to help secure the powerful talisman known as the silver spike.A sworn brother of the Black Company who held the rank of sergeant by the events of She Is the Darkness and master sergeant by Water Sleeps. He served under Sleepy throughout the Captivity, including the Kiaulune wars, and later during Water Sleeps and Soldiers Live. Sleepy considered him among the men she had known longest and trusted most, alongside Runmust Singh and Riverwalker, owing to his steadfast loyalty during the difficult years of the Kiaulune wars.A member of the Black Company who joined during its time in Hsien and appears in Soldiers Live. One of the Children of the Dead, he was distinguished by green eyes, a trait associated with demons in his home world. That unsettling feature supplied the Company nickname by which he is known.A mountain range of sandstone bluffs, pillars, and mesas in the northern continent, named after its single steep pass: an old road that climbs steeply through countless switchbacks, resembling from a distance a giant's lopsided stairway. The Windy Country lies immediately to its north, and the Tower at Charm, the capital of the Lady's Empire, lies not far to the south.Nicknamed Stance, the only child of the wizard Bomanz and his wife Jasmine, who appeared in the "flashback" biographic narrative of Bomanz in The White Rose. A minor wizard himself, he studied at the Black Campus of the university of Oar, where his father had studied decades before. His closest friend was Tokar, whose sister Glory he later became engaged to.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in the Annals during their service to the Lady's Empire, having previously served with the Company in Beryl and crossed the Sea of Torments aboard Soulcatcher's giant galley, The Dark Wings, to Opal. In the city of Oar, he was one of three men ordered by the sergeant Elmo to kill an informant working for the Limper's colonel, Zouad.A sworn brother of the Black Company during Shadows Linger, active during the Company's service to the Lady's Empire in the city of Juniper. He was part of an advance team of twenty-five Company men flown ahead of the main body into the city by the new Taken via flying carpet, alongside the physician and Annalist Croaker, the wizard Goblin, and other trusted soldiers. As the main Company force approached Juniper over the Wolander Mountains, Stork was sent ahead as a messenger to relay word to the Captain.One of the Ten Who Were Taken, the notorious sorcerer-enforcers first of the Dominator and later of the Lady. A woman of unimpressive stature and small frame, she possessed the fearsome ability to summon days-long, relentless storms, torrential downpours, and targeted lightning strikes from a clear sky, and proved equally formidable in unarmed combat.One of the four mysterious Shadowmasters who conquered the region later known as the Shadowlands in the southern continent. She seized the city of Jaicur and built a modern, heavily fortified city atop its ruins, renaming it Stormgard and making it her personal headquarters.A former Annalist of the Black Company who wrote the Book of Kette with Lees, Agrip, and Holm during the Company's second century, while it served the Paingod of Cho'n Delor. Croaker remembered him as "Old Straw" and "hell with a pen."One of the three Torque brothers, alongside Paddlefoot and Brother Bear, and a sworn member of the Black Company. The brothers came from the eastern region of the Lady's Empire, reported to the Lieutenant and Elmo, and remained loyal to Darling, whom they followed after the Battle of the Barrowland.A prostitute in Juniper who became romantically involved with Marron Shed, owner of the Iron Lily, during Shadows Linger. She cultivated expensive tastes and wore jewelry worth at least twenty leva, presenting a sharp contrast to Shed's precarious life in the impoverished Buskin. Shed became deeply enamored of her, making Sue an important presence in his personal life.The scholarly Master of the Taglian Royal Library during Water Sleeps. A member of the bhadralok, Taglios's high-caste but politically powerless Gunni intellectual class, he presided over a staff that included copyists such as Baladitya and the gatekeeper Adoo. Thoughtful and steeped in mythology, Santaraksita understood how ancient events could be transformed into powerful cultural symbols.The wife of the Black Company veteran Iqbal Singh, an attentive mother of their three children, and a loyal Company dependent throughout the final Books of Glittering Stone. An observant Shadar who considered herself unintelligent, she was nonetheless fondly regarded by both Annalists Sleepy and Croaker for her genuinely happy disposition and sense of humor, a rarity among the women attached to the Company. She and her family made the long journey south from Taglios with Sleepy's traveling party, through the Shadowgate and across the glittering plain, alongside her husband, brother-in-law Runmust, and their children.A young Shadowlander from the Sangel-speaking population of the southern continent. Short and chubby, he had been pushed unwillingly into military life by an embarrassed father and became a garrison commander in the Kiaulune region. His name means "Junior" in Sangel, giving him the sort of diminutive moniker commonly borne by Black Company soldiers.A member of the Nyueng Bao De Duang people and a student of Uncle Doj's Path of the Sword tradition. He served as the self-appointed bodyguard of the Black Company soldier Big Bucket, who initially refused his protection, and was a second cousin to the father of Ky Sahra and Thai Dei. He was among the Nyueng Bao Path of the Sword students who volunteered as bodyguards for members of the Old Crew after the Siege of Dejagore, out of gratitude for the Old Crew's role in protecting the surviving Nyueng Bao population.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned during the events of the short story "Bone Eaters," part of the On The Long Run arc.Colonel Sweet was the Monitor, or commander, of the Eternal Guard during The White Rose, a garrison permanently stationed near the Barrowland in the Great Forest whose sworn duty was to prevent the Dominator's escape and guard against any resurgence of the Resurrectionist cult. Before this posting he served in the armies of the Lady's Empire, including the campaign against the Rebel at the city of Rust. As Monitor, he struck up an unlikely friendship over chess and brandy with a laborer named Corbie, who did menial wage labor for his Guard subordinates.One of the four beautiful daughters of Baron Senjak and a murky figure associated with the beginning of the Domination era roughly five centuries before The Black Company. Sylith and her sisters were said to vie with one another in loveliness, placing her within the renowned aristocratic family surrounding that ancient age. Centuries later, she was discussed in The White Rose through fragmentary historical accounts.Master Sylus was captain of the Juniperen crew aboard the large oaken ship Cranky Bitch. Originally hired by Raven, he and his sailors participated in events surrounding Shadows Linger, though the Annals did not identify him by name until the later short story titled for his ship. His authority was maritime, rooted in command of the vessel and its crew.The ruler of Beryl, the oldest of the Jewel Cities, during Croaker's first chronicle, whom the Black Company served as personal bodyguards. A small man with a large hooked nose, he was the leader of the political faction known as the Reds, and ruled during a time of escalating internal unrest, caught between the demands of his own army, the Urban Cohorts, an opposition faction called the Blues, and the unpredictable masses of the city.The easternmost province of the Lady's Empire during Shadows Linger, Tally was a formerly independent kingdom described as a bleak land with only two substantial towns. Tome lay two thousand miles east of Charm and served as a garrison town, while Heart was the traditional seat of the Tallylander king. An arc of five massive cities (Rust, Frost, Ade, Barns, and Thud) stood to the west, with the still bleaker kingdom of Tambor to the northeast.A member of the Nyueng Bao De Duang people encountered in Bleak Seasons, who became the Speaker of their pilgrimage after his predecessor's passing. He survived the harrowing Siege of Dejagore and was introduced to Murgen of the Black Company by Ky Gota, continuing to collaborate with the Company on behalf of his people during their subsequent evacuation from the city. He spoke the Taglian language more fluently than Murgen.One of the Children of the Dead, a native of Hsien who joined the Black Company after the band took refuge in the Land of Unknown Shadows. Croaker described him as a trainee recruit, suggesting he had joined only shortly before the events of Soldiers Live.A sorcerer and member of the Circle of Eighteen, leading a significant Rebel force warring against the Imperial armies of the Lady and her generals, the Ten Who Were Taken, leading up to and during the events of The Black Company.Hired muscle for the wizard Abel, one of several freelance spike hunters competing to recover the silver spike in the besieged city of Oar during The Silver Spike, alongside his companions Shorts and Smiley.A cavalry officer of the Black Company during Soldiers Live, presumably one of the many Children of the Dead recruited in Hsien. He was present when the Company and their allies, the Unknown Shadows, captured and occupied the village of Gharhawnes in the former Shadowlands, where he and his troop stood picket duty outside the manor.A witch present in the besieged city of Oar during The Silver Spike, one of many freelance spike hunters competing to acquire the priceless silver spike hidden somewhere in the city. When the Imperial administrator Exile announced an offer to purchase the spike for 100,000 obols, Teebank was among a dozen independent hunters who countered with a higher bid of her own, offering 150,000.The name of both a language and its native people, once the primary tongue and ruling ethnic group of the Domination. Under the Dominator's reign, the TelleKurre were elevated far above all other groups in his empire. The language was rendered extinct following the White Rose Rebellion, when TelleKurre cities were burned and their populations scattered. A regional vulgate called UchiTelle was also spoken. The spelling of TelleKurre names was notoriously free-form, with various letter combinations representing identical sounds.Ten notorious sorcerers of very high magnitude enslaved by the Dominator about five centuries before The Black Company. They served as his generals during the Domination and were later imprisoned with him and the Lady in the Barrowland. Their translated TelleKurre names include Soulcatcher, the Limper, the Howler, Shapeshifter, Stormbringer, the Hanged Man, Bonegnasher, Nightcrawler, Moonbiter, and the Faceless Man.A thug working for the gangster Krage in the Buskin, the most downtrodden slum of the city of Juniper, during Shadows Linger.A Nyueng Bao man, the brother of Ky Sahra, and the devoted bodyguard of the Black Company mainstay Murgen. Though never a sworn member of the Company, he remained a loyal ally for many years. A man of few words, he was widely recognized for his excellent swordsmanship and devotion to the Path of the Sword, exceeded in skill only by the master Uncle Doj. Murgen described him as short, skinny, lantern-jawed, taciturn, and surly, with crudely cropped black hair. He became Murgen's bodyguard after the Siege of Dejagore, out of gratitude for the Old Crew's role in saving the surviving Nyueng Bao population.A member of the Nyueng Bao De Duang people and a Path of the Sword disciple who became the bodyguard of Black Company wizard Goblin. Reticent by nature and initially able to speak only a handful of words of the Taglian language, he accompanied Goblin on the Shaded Road commando expedition during She Is the Darkness, a mission through his own home swamps of the Nyueng Bao delta and across the inhospitable Shindai Kus desert to mobilize fighters loyal to the Black Company.A young, overweight, unmotivated wizard from Aloe who served as an apprentice to both One-Eye and Goblin during the Black Company's time in that city, chronicled in Port of Shadows. Though "talented in the extreme" and literate in Aloen, he showed little investment in his own potential or in Company affairs. He called himself "the Third" because he used the same cover name as both his father and grandfather before him, though Croaker never disclosed what that name was.A soldier of the Black Company mentioned in Port of Shadows. The Annals associate the enigmatic phrase "A cowbird's egg in a nest of lies" with his name but preserve no explanation. Nothing further is recorded about his background, appearance, or Company service.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned only once in the Annals, during the Company's time at the city of Lords. There, the Annalist Croaker mused on how a giggling, inquisitive toddler could grow up to become a hardened, dangerous man like Three Fingers.A sworn brother of the Black Company active during the Juniper campaign of Shadows Linger. He was part of an advance team of twenty-five Company men flown ahead of the main body into the city by the new Taken via flying carpet, alongside the physician and Annalist Croaker, the wizard Goblin, and other trusted soldiers. Along with Sharkey, Kingpin, and Pawnbroker, Tickle was assigned to keep watch over Marron Shed, the owner of the Iron Lily tavern, under cover as a sailor who had missed his ship.A holy prostitute of an established cult in the prosperous city of Aloe, chronicled early in Port of Shadows. Along with at least fifteen other women, she lived in the massive Aloen temple of Occupoa, where the cult's members sold their services to raise funds and trained to read ancient sacred texts in several liturgical languages. A nascent sorceress, she unconsciously emitted an enchantment that caused those around her, especially men, to become overwhelmingly attracted and loyal to her.The mangy mongrel companion of the mysterious soldier Tracker, encountered by the Black Company in The White Rose. Despite his ordinary canine appearance, his unnervingly red eyes and unnatural resilience hinted that he was far more than he seemed, capable of holding his own even against several of the new Taken.A boy of mixed Nyueng Bao and northern ancestry who appears in the Books of Glittering Stone. He was born with an unusually strong natural aptitude for sorcery, described by One-Eye as a large hybrid talent. Calm, inquisitive, and patient by nature, Tobo approached the magical world with unusual focus for his age.An antiquities seller in the major city of Oar, known for a bluff, honest, and irreverent manner despite his outwardly jovial nature and respectful treatment of business partners. He appeared in the "flashback" biographic narrative of the wizard Bomanz in The White Rose.Two of the fifteen or sixteen surviving members of the Voroshk ruling clan after their world was invaded by shadows in Soldiers Live. The two youngest of their family, they were posted by their elders to guard the ruins of their world's shadowgate at Rhuknavr, watching for the return of a missing young kinswoman of the Family.A minor wizard and sworn brother of the Black Company, and its second-oldest member for many decades. Nicknamed for the small drum he frequently rapped upon to punctuate his speech, he and his blood brother One-Eye were small, ancient black men from the jungles of D'loc Aloc, both trained in the art of illusions under the same master, N'Gamo. Tom-Tom led a small party of Company men to investigate rumors of a centuries-old forvalaka loose in the city of Beryl, drawing on his former master's own costly encounter with one of the creatures years before.A card game so central to the culture of the Black Company that Croaker described it as a tradition that "began ages before my time" and would "persist long after I am gone." Wherever the Company halts for even fifteen minutes, a tonk game tends to develop. Croaker characterized it as "one of the simplest games ever invented, rules-wise," but noted that the table talk accompanying play is as essential as the cards themselves. Small stakes were common, and banter between players was expected. The wizard One-Eye was infamously poor at the game unless he was cheating, and was known to squander considerable sums as a result.Three blood brothers named Brother Bear, Paddlefoot, and Stubby, all sworn members of the Black Company. The trio entered the brotherhood during its association with the New White Rose Rebellion. Their shared service and close family identity made them a recognizable unit within the otherwise loosely related mercenary band.A fierce and mysterious fighter encountered in The White Rose who became an ally of the Black Company and Darling's rebellion. Tall and muscular, he arrived on the Plain of Fear as a western courier accompanied by his hound, Toadkiller Dog. His extraordinary archery and intense attachment to the dog made him a striking but unsettling companion.A regional warlord of Hsien and member of the File of Nine during Soldiers Live. One of the Children of the Dead, he wore a mask during the council's anonymous meetings. Despite sharing the common surname Tran with several other warlords, he had no familial relationship to them.A regional warlord of Hsien and member of the File of Nine during Soldiers Live. One of the Children of the Dead, he wore a mask during the council's anonymous meetings. Despite sharing the common surname Tran with several other warlords, he had no familial relationship to them.A regional warlord of Hsien and member of the File of Nine during Soldiers Live. One of the Children of the Dead, he wore a mask during the council's anonymous meetings. Despite sharing the common surname Tran with several other warlords, he had no familial relationship to them.A regional warlord of Hsien and member of the File of Nine during Soldiers Live. One of the Children of the Dead, he wore a mask during the council's anonymous meetings. Despite sharing the common surname Tran with several other warlords, he had no familial relationship to them.The newest and youngest member of the File of Nine, a council of regional warlords of Hsien, during Soldiers Live, identified as "the Last Entered of the File" and wearing a mask surmounted by a carved crane's head during their anonymous meetings. Despite the shared surname "Tran," he had no family relation to his fellow members.A female sorcerer and member of the Circle of Eighteen, leading a significant Rebel force warring against the Lady and her Imperial forces under the Ten Who Were Taken. Trinket and her force fought a grueling three-year campaign alongside fellow Circle sorceress Whisper around the eastern city of Rust.A sworn brother of the Black Company and one of Sleepy's officers during Soldiers Live. He came from a province of Hsien where flowery styles of speech were highly valued, and Croaker considered him "another of those fiercely competent professional officers who had wanted to shed the feudal chains of Hsien in hopes of making his fortune."Sir Tucker was a knight from Rust mentioned during the opening events of The White Rose. A bitter enemy of the Lady and her Empire, he was regarded as the most dedicated locally embedded agent of Darling's New White Rose Rebellion. Croaker wrote that Tucker's hatred of the Empire knew no bounds.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned once in the Annals, during the Company's garrison in Aloe in Port of Shadows. He and Reams assisted the wizard Silent in a mission for the Company, having apparently enlisted sometime before the group's arrival in the region.A thief appearing in The Silver Spike and member of a four-man criminal group. The available page provides no safe introductory information about his origins, appearance, personality, or earlier life.A sworn brother of the Black Company who appeared during the events of the short story "Bone Eaters," part of the On The Long Run arc. Croaker described him as "none too bright" and very young.The nickname of Shoré Chodroze, an Imperial colonel and sorcerer of "almost Taken caliber" in service to the Lady's Empire. He arrived in the city of Aloe with his bodyguard, Buzz, to determine whether the Black Company had uncovered a dangerous prophecy tied to the Dominator, and to destroy it if so. His nickname originated from an insult by the Company's Lieutenant, who declared he "wasn't worth two dead flies."Thousands of magical entities native to Hsien, also called the hidden folk. They ranged from small or humanlike forms to creatures resembling animals and nightmares, often seeming present only when an observer looked away. Unlike the feral shadows of the glittering plain, they were cunning, wicked, individual, and capable of reason, though notably poor at cooperation.A Taglian gang enforcer who came into conflict with the Black Company before Water Sleeps. He had a distinctive, unsettling smile and what Sleepy described as a reptilian lack of connection to other people. Remarkably fearless, he seemed too dense to understand fear in personal terms, giving him an unnerving reputation.A serving woman who worked at the Palace of Taglios in Water Sleeps. She was apprehended by the Greys, the Protectorate's police force, after attempting to steal a small silver oil lamp.A Black Company sergeant from Hsien during Soldiers Live, one of twenty-six "brightest and most trusted youngsters" of the reconstituted Company, all described as pathfinders and rangers. Serving under Blade at Shivetya's fortress, his mission was to help retrieve troves of ancient treasure from the caverns deep beneath the glittering plain, which Sleepy intended to use to finance the coming war against the Protectorate.The grandfather of the managing family of the Mole Tavern in Beryl, and a member or sympathizer of the political faction known as the Blues.A member of the Black Company during the events of Water Sleeps, known for a foul mouth that drew a quick rebuke from Sleepy the first time he was mentioned. Using one of the Company's few remaining fireball projectors, Vigan led an attack on a fortified position along the way to the Shadowgate, with Sleepy placing him in charge of ten other Company men for the operation.A sentient, talking buzzard from the Plain of Fear who appears in The Silver Spike. His species was one of roughly forty intelligent creature kinds native to that strange region, alongside menhirs, mantas, and windwhales. Fluent in Forsberger, Virgil was irreverent, relentlessly foul-mouthed, and inclined to heckle those around him.A sworn brother of the Black Company who served during the band's contract with the Syndic of Beryl, prior to the opening events of The Black Company.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned in Shadows Linger, active during the Company's service to the Lady's Empire in the city of Juniper. He was part of an advance team of twenty-five Company men flown ahead of the main body into the city by the new Taken via flying carpet, alongside the physician and Annalist Croaker, the wizard Goblin, and other trusted soldiers. He was later stationed in the Wolander Mountains alongside Croaker, Otto, and others to guard the pathway to the black castle.A resident of the Buskin, Juniper's impoverished slum, and a cousin of Marron Shed in Shadows Linger. He lived with his wife Sal, their children, and his mother in a tiny one-room apartment. Shed occasionally hired Wally out of pity for Sal to help at the Iron Lily, where he performed odd tasks and sometimes stood in as barkeeper despite Shed considering him a ne'er-do-well.A sworn brother of the Black Company mentioned briefly in Water Sleeps. He played a minor role when the Company peacefully subdued a group of about fifty Protectorate-aligned Shadowlanders who had marched out from Kiaulune to confront them, helping ensure the captives were properly restrained after they surrendered their weapons.A city or town in the eastern reaches of the Lady's Empire in the northern continent, mentioned once in the Annals by Soulcatcher. Site of a notable battle between Soulcatcher, the most powerful of the Ten Who Were Taken, and Whisper, the most dangerous Rebel leader of the Circle of Eighteen. Soulcatcher cited Were alongside Rust and the Plain of Fear as locations where she had faced Whisper directly.A sworn brother of the Black Company notorious for his ceaseless respiratory problems, who joined the group in Shadow Games and went on to feature in the first two Books of Glittering Stone. Summoned by monks of the Temple of Travellers' Repose to serve as a guide during the Company's journey south, Wheezer was a short, elderly, "wizened" native of D'loc Aloc, nicknamed for his chronic cough, the result of consumption and a lifelong habit of chewing the narcotic root qat. Croaker wrote that he was "thrilled" Wheezer had joined, calling him "a second-rate soul son of One-Eye, full of ridiculous mischief."A sorcerer and member of the Circle of Eighteen, leading a significant Rebel force warring against the Imperial armies of the Lady and her generals, the Ten Who Were Taken, leading up to and during the events of The Black Company.A formidable sorceress and leading member of the Circle of Eighteen, likely hailing from the eastern city of Rust. A talented general, she fought ferocious campaigns against Soulcatcher and the armies of the Lady's Empire for years, forcing a bloody stalemate in the east, and was known for a melodious voice strikingly at odds with her wide, hard, and homely appearance.A legendary woman whose rebellion ended the era in the northern continent known as the Domination, defeating the Dominator, his wife the Lady, and the Ten Who Were Taken roughly 370 years before the establishment of the Lady's Empire. She directed her campaigns from the Great Forest and was regarded as one of the greatest generals ever to live, ultimately sealing her enemies away rather than destroying them outright.A sworn brother of the Black Company who appeared in the first chronicle, active during the band's contract with the Syndic of Beryl and throughout their first year of service in the Lady's Empire. He was on sentry duty when he first spotted the massive black galley, The Dark Wings, in Beryl's harbor, and later accompanied a squad investigating a village in Forsberg province that had been razed by the Limper's forces.A sworn brother of the Black Company who appears in several short stories of the On The Long Run arc, most prominently "Shaggy Dog Bridge." He earned his nickname for his constant habit of whittling small, ugly carvings from any available wood, and his thick provincial accent was transcribed verbatim by Croaker in the Annals. Though Croaker called him "a strange little man," Whittle frequently volunteered for risky reconnaissance missions and was undaunted by the belligerent newcomer Rusty.A sworn brother of the Black Company who served during the band's contract with the Syndic of Beryl, prior to the opening events of The Black Company.Brigadier Wildbrand was the commanding officer of the elite Nightstalker Brigade, "the crack outfit in the northern army, rigorously trained for night operations and combat under wizard's war conditions," and a key figure in the events of The Silver Spike. She and her soldiers were ordered by the twin sorcerers Gossamer and Spidersilk to search the city of Oar for the silver spike, a task she executed loyally despite resenting being used as the twins' personal enforcers.A sworn brother of the Black Company who appears only once in the Annals, during the first chronicle, early in the Company's service to the Lady's Empire. During the Company's first winter at the fortress of Meystrikt in the province of the Salient, Willie was one of the men who joked with Croaker about the Annalist's florid speculations regarding their mysterious employer, the Lady.A long-haired, blond army deserter from the city of Roses who first crossed paths with the Black Company in Shadow Games. He and his two close friends, Cordy Mather and Blade, were hired by the royal siblings of Taglios, the Prahbrindrah Drah and the Radisha Drah, to organize the city's first armed resistance against the initial invasion attempts of the Shadowmasters. Swan's father was a hod carrier; after deserting from military service in Roses, Swan drifted south with Cordy Mather, rescuing Blade along the way, and the three eventually settled in Taglios to run a brewery before meeting the Black Company.A soldier of the Black Company mentioned in Port of Shadows. The Annals preserve only a cryptic observation associated with his name, without explaining its context. No details about his origin, appearance, personality, or service are otherwise recorded.Sentient flying beasts native to the Plain of Fear, windwhales resemble an enormous cross between a man-of-war jellyfish and a shark when viewed from below. Some exceed five hundred yards in length and one hundred yards in width, with broad, creviced backs inhabited by symbiotic manta colonies. Carnivorous and equipped with immense tentacles capable of seizing horses or pulverizing buildings, they fly using flammable gas that makes fire their principal vulnerability.An inhospitable northern desert west of the Plain of Fear and east of the Forest of Cloud and Lords. Described as a vast emptiness where the wind blows constantly, it has no fixed tracks and was considered worthless by the Lady's Empire. Its deep canyons could provide cover, but travel across its exposed wastes was punishing and dangerous.A sworn brother of the Black Company from the southern continent who appears in Bleak Seasons. A rank-and-file soldier, he took part in the Company's expedition to the Grove of Doom. The Annals preserve no further personal detail about his appearance, temperament, or earlier service.A Jaicuri stonemason from Dejagore who became a sworn brother of the Black Company during its southern campaigns. His civilian trade and local origins distinguished him among the soldiers drawn into the Company's ranks around the Shadowmaster wars. The Annalist Murgen remembered him as a fellow brother from that difficult period.A major mountain range in the far northwest of the northern continent. Two snow-topped arms enclose Juniper and the Port River valley, with Duretile on the southern heights and the black castle on the northern. The range extends east of Juniper for at least one hundred miles and reaches the sea to the west.A teenage bandit from a small clan west of Rue and the brother of Haru. He was a loyal cousin of the young witch Chasing Midnight, her twin Chasing Moonlight, Chick, and Fade in the short story "Bone Eaters." A string of hardships had pushed the closely bound young relatives into amateur banditry.An archer and sworn brother of the Black Company during the events of "Leta of the Thousand Sorrows" and "Shaggy Dog Bridge," two short stories of the On The Long Run arc. One of the young recruits from the city of Chimney, he served as a messenger under Elmo's orders and later joined a reconnaissance team that discovered a centuries-old, sorcery-hidden bridge over the geological formation known as the Rip.Duke Zimerlan was the hereditary ruler of Juniper, an independent city-state in the far northwest of the northern continent, before and during Shadows Linger. He governed from Duretile and inherited knowledge of the lethal black rock his ancestors had discovered roughly four centuries earlier, a shunned object that gradually grew into the mysterious black castle. As the castle's expansion accelerated, Zimerlan contacted the Lady for help investigating and eliminating it, bringing Juniper's Custodians, Inquisitors, and powerful Imperial visitors together to address the threat.A colonel in the Limper's army of the Lady's Empire during The Black Company. He served as the Taken sorcerer's political liaison and favorite enforcer, combining military rank with a role in the Limper's coercive political affairs. Captain Lane was among the officers reporting directly to him.